"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720261","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-04-25","<p>The Department's English Housing Survey estimates that, in 2015-16, 20 per cent of households in England live in the private rented sector. This equates to about 4.5 million households. Estimates are not available for constituency and the Department does not publish regional estimates.</p><p>A table with data for the last 10 years can be found here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/501068/2014-15_Section_1_Households_tables_and_figures_FINAL.xlsx" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/595786/2015-16_Section_1_Households_Annex_Tables.xlsx</a>. See AT1.1.</p>","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell",,"2017-04-25T10:31:59.65Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720261/answer","Biography information for Lord Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720261/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720261/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-04-13","Private Rented Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many people were living in the private rented sector (a) in absolute terms and (b) as a proportion of the population in (i) England, (ii) the West Midlands and (iii) Birmingham Northfield constituency in each of the last 10 years.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","70894"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720262","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-04-25","<p>Any plans will be for a future govenment to make.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-04-25T16:10:46.34Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720262/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720262/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720262/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-04-13","Children: Dental Health","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, whether his Department is planning or undertaking any work to co-ordinate local authority programmes for improving children's oral health.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","70856"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720263","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-04-25","<p>The Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government makes appointments to the Board of the Homes and Communities Agency. The Office of the Commissioner for Public Appointments and the Parliamentary Secretary (Minister for the Constitution) Chris Skidmore MP, maintain an overview of all public appointments. The Cabinet Office Public Appointments team provide advice as required at each stage of the process.</p><p>The selection panel for each appointment comprises the Chair of the Board, a senior official from the Department for Communities and Local Government and an independent member with no direct link to the Homes and Communities Agency.</p>","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell",,"2017-04-25T14:29:12.52Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720263/answer","Biography information for Lord Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720263/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720263/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-04-13","Homes and Communities Agency: Public Appointments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, who makes appointments to the Board of the Homes and Communities Agency; which other organisations or individuals provide advice on those appointments; and at what stage of the process such advice is provided.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","70863"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720264","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-04-27","<p>It has not proved possible to respond to the hon. Member in the time available before Prorogation.</p>","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell",,"2017-04-27T08:57:14.19Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720264/answer","Biography information for Lord Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720264/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720264/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-04-13","Letting Agents: North East","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, for what reasons no venue in the North East was chosen for a letting agents' fees ban workshop.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","70913"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720265","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-04-26","<p>We have already taken steps to tackle rogue and unfair practices by private parking operators, including the banning of wheel clamping and towing.</p><p>Private parking companies receive DVLA data on the condition that it will only be used to help follow up alleged parking contraventions. It cannot be further processed for any other purpose. The audit by the Information Commissioner’s Office in March 2016, judged the DVLA’s procedures to offer high assurance that processes to mitigate the risks of non-compliance with the Data Protection Act are in place.</p><p> </p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-04-26T10:48:28.23Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720265/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720265/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720265/answer","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720265/answer/previousversion/44889","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-04-13","Parking: Fees and Charges","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, pursuant to the Answer of 20 March 2017 to Question 68027, when his Department plans to respond to the discussion paper, Parking reform: tackling unfair practices.","false","Biography information for Tom Blenkinsop","Middlesbrough South and East Cleveland","Tom Blenkinsop","70927"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720266","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-04-24","<p>It is for those commissioning building work to decide whether to employ a clerk of works to evaluate or supervise the building work they wish to carry out. In many cases architects, structural and civil engineers and other professionals are used as an alternative to a clerk of works.</p>","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell",,"2017-04-24T14:28:48.347Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720266/answer","Biography information for Lord Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720266/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720266/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-04-13","Building Regulations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what use is made of Clerks of Works in evaluating building projects.","false","Biography information for Oliver Colvile","Plymouth, Sutton and Devonport","Oliver Colvile","70929"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720267","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-04-25","<p>The Tenancy Deposit Schemes in England currently protect over 3 million deposits on behalf of tenants, helping to raise standards in the private rented sector and ensuring that tenants are treated fairly at the end of their tenancy.</p><p>If there is a dispute about the amount of the deposit to be returned, the tenant and the landlord can either agree to use the free Alternative Dispute Resolution (ADR) service provided by the Tenancy Deposit Protection schemes or go to court. Where both the landlord and tenant agree to using the ADR service the case will be handled by an independent, impartial and qualified Adjudicator, and a decision will be made within 28 days. The deposit is the tenant’s money and landlords should be prepared to provide appropriate evidence where they believe they are entitled to retain any of the deposit.</p><p>Of the 13.2 million deposits which have been protected since the launch of the scheme, less than 1.5 per cent have gone to adjudication.</p>","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell",,"2017-04-25T14:30:11.433Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720267/answer","Biography information for Lord Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720267/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720267/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-04-13","Tenancy Deposit Schemes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, whether his Department has carried out a review of (a) misuses of tenancy deposit schemes by landlords in order to delay or reduce amounts reimbursed and (b) the merits of requiring the landlord rather than the tenant to submit an appeal for deposit money.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","70892"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720268","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-04-25","<p>At present, no additional workshops are planned.</p>","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell",,"2017-04-25T10:28:38.827Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720268/answer","Biography information for Lord Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720268/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720268/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-04-13","Letting Agents: North East","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if he will host additional workshops in the North East on letting agents' fees.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","70911"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720269","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-04-27","<p>I will ask the Chief Executive of the Homes and Communities Agency to write to the hon. Member with this information.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell",,"2017-04-27T09:08:51.643Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720269/answer","Biography information for Lord Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720269/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720269/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-04-13","Homes and Communities Agency: Public Appointments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what proportion of the Homes and Communities Agency Board are (a) women, (b) from black or minority ethnic backgrounds, (c) disabled or (d) from lower socio-economic backgrounds.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","70719"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720270","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-04-25","<p>This Government has committed to increasing the take-up of brownfield sites for development, especially for new homes. Our National Planning Policy Framework asks local authorities to encourage re-use of brownfield sites wherever practicable, and the law now requires each local authority to maintain a register of local brownfield sites suitable for housing. However, for a brownfield site to be suitable to redevelop, it should not be of high environmental value. In the Government’s view, this policy is clear to decision-makers, and we see no reason to amend the Framework, or to limit the freedom of local communities to judge how to apply national policy to the facts of particular cases.</p>","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell",,"2017-04-25T14:26:23.79Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720270/answer","Biography information for Lord Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720270/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720270/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-04-13","Derelict Land","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, with reference to paragraph 111 of the National Planning Policy Framework published by his Department in March 2012, what his policy is on the development of brownfield land classified as being of high environmental value; and whether he has plans to amend paragraph 111 of the National Planning Policy Framework in order to (a) limit and (b) prohibit such development.","false","Biography information for Kelly Tolhurst","Rochester and Strood","Kelly Tolhurst","70715"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720271","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-04-25","<p>The Department does not issue guidance or collect data on the number of shared services between local authorities and other parts of the public sector.</p><p>However, the Local Government Association undertakes an annual survey of shared services in local government. It estimates that at least 96 per cent of councils across the country currently share services. Since 2012, sharing arrangements such as these have delivered over half a billion pounds of savings across local government.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-04-25T10:24:01.953Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720271/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720271/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720271/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-04-13","Local Government Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what estimate he has made of the number of shared services between local authorities and other parts of the public sector; and what guidance his Department gives to local authorities to encourage them to collaborate and share services with others wherever possible.","false","Biography information for Craig Whittaker","Calder Valley","Craig Whittaker","70836"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720272","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-04-27","<p>Sunderland’s Core Spending Power was £232 million in 2015-16 and will be £231 million in 2019-20. The 4 year settlement means councils can plan ahead with confidence.</p><p>Local authorities are independent of central government and are responsible for managing their budgets in line with local priorities. Local spending decisions are better made by people who understand their communities and who are best placed to make the right call.</p><p>Sunderland City Council, like other councils, have continued to balance their budget while reducing council tax in real terms and maintaining public satisfaction with services.</p><p>The Spending Review took account of the costs of delivery of essential services and set out a sustainable basis for local authorities to discharge their functions. In addition, Spring Budget 2017 announced a further £2 billion funding in England to spend on adult social care over the next 3 years, of which Sunderland was allocated over £14 million over the next 3 years.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-04-27T09:07:08.653Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720272/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720272/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720272/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-04-13","Local Government Finance: Sunderland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what assessment he has made of the potential effect of reductions in local authority funding on Sunderland City Council's delivery of essential services.","false","Biography information for Julie Elliott","Sunderland Central","Julie Elliott","70830"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720273","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-04-20","<p>Defra does not hold information on the number of staff who have been employed by local authorities with responsibility for air quality.</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-04-20T16:44:18.273Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720273/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720273/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720273/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-04-13","Air Pollution","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what information her Department holds on the number of staff who have been employed by local authorities with a responsibility for air quality in each of the last 10 years.","false","Biography information for Sue Hayman","Workington","Sue Hayman","70783"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720274","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-04-20","<p>Defra does not hold information on the amount which has been spent by local authorities on monitoring and improving air quality in each of the last ten years.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-04-20T16:41:54.48Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720274/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720274/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720274/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-04-13","Air Pollution","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what information her Department holds on the amount which has been spent by local authorities on monitoring and improving air quality in each of the last 10 years.","false","Biography information for Sue Hayman","Workington","Sue Hayman","70751"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720275","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-04-24","<p>The statutory guidance in Approved Document C (Site preparation and resistance to contaminants and moisture) which supports the Building Regulations promotes the use of flood resilience and resistance measures in flood prone areas. The document references guidance produced jointly by the Department for Communities and Local Government, Defra and the Environment Agency – <em>Improving the flood performance of new buildings – Flood resilient construction</em>. Much of the information is applicable to resilient repair as well as new build.</p><p>The Building Regulations also require that floors, roof and walls of buildings should be adequately protected from harmful effects caused by spillage of water from or associated with sanitary fittings or fixed appliance. Guidance on how to meet this requirement is set out in Approved Document C.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell",,"2017-04-24T14:47:09.303Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720275/answer","Biography information for Lord Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720275/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720275/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-04-13","Housing: Construction","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, whether he plans to strengthen provisions in building regulations on ensuring that materials and methods used in housing construction are more resilient to the risk of flooding and damage caused by water leaks.","false","Biography information for Oliver Colvile","Plymouth, Sutton and Devonport","Oliver Colvile","70791"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720276","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-04-27","<p>In March we published a Government Review: Making Commercial Terms of Government Land Disposals More Transparent. The report committed to publish details of Government land sales annually, with the first publication in summer 2017. The report will include all sales in 2015/16 and 2016/17.</p><p>Progress towards meeting the housing ambition is set out in Table 3 of the Public Land for Housing Programme Annual Report published in February 2017 which shows that between 8 May 2015 and 30 September 2016, DCLG released land with capacity for 6,618 homes, generating £145,783,417 in receipts.</p><p>As a major landowner the Government has a crucial role to play in managing its estate more efficiently to secure best value for money for the taxpayer, boost growth and help support the building of new homes.</p>","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell",,"2017-04-27T10:44:48.44Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720276/answer","Biography information for Lord Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720276/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720276/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-04-13","Department for Communities and Local Government: Land","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, with reference to paragraphs 1.296 and 1.297 of the Spending Review and Autumn Statement 2015, what progress his Department has made by estimated capacity of land sold since March 2016 in identifying and disposing of land to meet the Government's commitment.","false","Biography information for Mr Mark Prisk","Hertford and Stortford","Mr Mark Prisk","70672"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720277","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-04-25","<p>Private parking companies receive DVLA data on the condition that it will only be used to help follow up alleged parking contraventions. It cannot be further processed for any other purpose. The audit by the Information Commissioner’s Office in March 2016, judged the DVLA’s procedures to offer high assurance that processes to mitigate the risks of non-compliance with the Data Protection Act are in place. My Department has no plans to carry out a review.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-04-25T14:19:57.593Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720277/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720277/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720277/answer","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720277/answer/previousversion/44887","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-04-13","Parking: Private Sector","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if he will discuss with the Department of Transport, the DVLA and the trades associations for private car parking companies reviewing the regulations for the passing of information gained from the DVLA Vehicle Keeper Database by private car parking companies to third parties as part of his Department's consideration of its approach to future Government intervention in the area of private car parking companies.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","70658"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720278","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-04-20","<p>We expect all housing to be of good quality and to avoid a race to the bottom in size. Building regulations are there to ensure new homes are safe, secure and sustainable.</p><p>The White Paper 'Fixing our broken housing market' is clear that it is important that we deliver a range of housing types and tenures to meet a range of housing needs. As part of this the permitted development right for the change of use from office to residential is making a valuable contribution to the delivery of new homes, having delivered over 12,800 homes in the year to March 2016.</p><p> </p>","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell",,"2017-04-20T14:10:34.287Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720278/answer","Biography information for Lord Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720278/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720278/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-04-13","Change of Use","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, whether his Department has made an assessment of the effect on (a) local infrastructure and (b) human health of the conversion of offices into small flats from 16 square metres in size.","false","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","Chipping Barnet","Mrs Theresa Villiers","70643"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720279","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-04-21","<p>The Road Traffic (Vehicle Emissions) (Fixed Penalty) (England) Regulations 2002 enable local authorities to issue £20 Fixed Penalty Notices (FPNs) to drivers leaving engines running unnecessarily after being asked to turn off the engine. The decision to issue FPNs is at the discretion of local authorities, which may authorise any officer of the authority or any other person, to undertake this function.</p><p> </p><p>Local authorities also have a statutory duty to publish air quality plans to demonstrate their efforts towards reducing local air pollution, including that caused by unnecessary engine idling.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-04-21T11:21:03.363Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720279/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720279/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720279/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-04-13","Air Pollution: Cars","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what powers local authorities have to tackle air pollution caused by idling cars near schools and other public areas.","false","Biography information for Alex Chalk","Cheltenham","Alex Chalk","70478"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720280","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-04-25","<p>The campaign for the last Homes and Communities Agency Board member recruitment, in August 2016, received seventy three applications.</p>","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell",,"2017-04-25T10:26:13.563Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720280/answer","Biography information for Lord Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720280/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720280/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-04-13","Homes and Communities Agency: Public Appointments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many applications the board of the Home and Communities Agency received during its last intake.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","70497"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720281","Department for Transport","false","2017-04-24","<p>None. It is for local authorities to assess the effectiveness of their local policies on their local communities.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2017-04-24T12:56:48.877Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720281/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720281/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720281/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-04-13","Parking: Fees and Charges","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment he has made of the effectiveness of the policies operated by local authorities on parking charges in supporting the local economy whilst adequately managing traffic and parking flows.","false","Biography information for Craig Whittaker","Calder Valley","Craig Whittaker","70584"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720282","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-04-27","<p>As of 31 March 2017 the Department had 1453 total staff directly employed on the payroll broken down by the following employment classificiations, full time/part time status and length of contract:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td rowspan="2"><p><strong>Employment Class</strong></p></td><td colspan="2"><p><strong>Full Time</strong></p></td><td colspan="2"><p><strong>Part Time</strong></p></td><td rowspan="2"><p><strong>Total Count</strong></p></td><td rowspan="2"><p><strong>Total %</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Count</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>%</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Count</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>%</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Permanent</p></td><td><p>1168</p></td><td><p>80.4%</p></td><td><p>155</p></td><td><p>10.7%</p></td><td><p>1323</p></td><td><p>91.1%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Fixed Term Appt (0 - 2 Years)</p></td><td><p>88</p></td><td><p>6.1%</p></td><td><p>5</p></td><td><p>0.3%</p></td><td><p>93</p></td><td><p>6.4%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Fixed Term Appt (2+ Years)</p></td><td><p>1</p></td><td><p>0.1%</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>0.0%</p></td><td><p>1</p></td><td><p>0.1%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Paid Loan In (0 - 2 Years)</p></td><td><p>31</p></td><td><p>2.1%</p></td><td><p>1</p></td><td><p>0.1%</p></td><td><p>32</p></td><td><p>2.2%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Paid Secondment In (0-2 Years)</p></td><td><p>1</p></td><td><p>0.1%</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>0.0%</p></td><td><p>1</p></td><td><p>0.1%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Paid Loan In (2+ Years)</p></td><td><p>3</p></td><td><p>0.2%</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>0.0%</p></td><td><p>3</p></td><td><p>0.2%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Grand Total</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>1292</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>88.9%</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>161</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>11.1%</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>1453</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>100.0%</strong></p></td></tr></tbody></table><p><br>Separately, the Department had three members of staff employed on an agency basis at the same date, however these staff are not included in the payroll headcount and as such are not presented as a proportion of the Department's total staffing.</p><p>The Department has no employees working on zero-hours contracts.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-04-27T09:26:09.55Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720282/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720282/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720282/answer","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720282/answer/previousversion/44885","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-04-13","Department for Communities and Local Government: Conditions of Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many and what proportion of staff employed by his Department are employed on a contract which is (a) full-time permanent, (b) part-time permanent, (c) for less than two years' duration, (d) on an agency basis and (e) zero-hours.","false","Biography information for Rob Marris","Wolverhampton South West","Rob Marris","70602"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720283","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-04-27","<p>It has not proved possible to respond to the hon. Member in the time available before Prorogation.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-04-27T08:56:00.38Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720283/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720283/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720283/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-04-13","Department for Communities and Local Government: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, pursuant to the Answer of 6 March 2017 to Question 64994, on procurement, what estimate he has made of the amount spent on procurement management in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","70546"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720284","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-04-25","<p>The 2012 reinvigorated Right to Buy scheme increased maximum discounts to realistic levels and, for the first time ever, introduced a requirement that for every additional sale, a new affordable home would be provided. There is a rolling 3 year deadline for local authorities to deliver additional affordable homes under the reinvigorated Right to Buy, and so far they have delivered within profile.</p><p>Under the terms of the voluntary Right to Buy agreement, housing associations have also committed to provide an additional home for each property sold on a one-for-one basis – increasing overall housing supply. Housing associations know their customers’ needs best and we envisage that new build would reflect the local market conditions.</p><p>Right to Buy discounts are set nationally, which provides an equal, easy to understand offer to tenants. The maximum discounts are higher in London as London is a unique market, where property prices are generally significantly above those in other areas, which makes it more difficult for tenants to take up their Right to Buy.</p>","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell",,"2017-04-25T10:27:09.957Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720284/answer","Biography information for Lord Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720284/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720284/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-04-13","Right to Buy Scheme: Affordable Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, with reference to page 78 of the Joseph Rowntree Foundation report, entitled UK Poverty: Causes and Solutions, if he will make it his policy to replace all homes sold under right to buy with low cost rented properties ensuring that there is a local discretion over size of discount and eligibility for all types of right to buy.","false","Biography information for Lyn Brown","West Ham","Lyn Brown","70560"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720285","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-04-25","<p>The first year of the Community Housing Fund was distributed through local authorities and used to build capacity within local groups. Funding for 2017/18 will be used to deliver housing on the ground for local people.</p>","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell",,"2017-04-25T10:38:06.477Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720285/answer","Biography information for Lord Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720285/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720285/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-04-13","Affordable Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, whether the Community Housing Fund will continue to be distributed through local authorities from 2017-18.","false","Biography information for Dr Sarah Wollaston","Totnes","Dr Sarah Wollaston","70575"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720286","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-04-20","<p>Following leaseholders’ concerns about high service charges for capital works programmes, the Department for Communities and Local Government introduced <em>The Social Landlords Mandatory Reduction of Service Charges (England) Direction 2014 </em>which capped service charges payable by local authority leaseholders in respect of major works funded, in whole or in part, by Government.</p><p>Local Government has legal duties to remain compliant with the law.</p><p>Leaseholders can challenge service charges for major works in the First-tier Tribunal (Property Chamber) including where works are not recoverable under the lease, charges are not reasonable, or have not been carried out to a reasonable standard. In addition,<em> The Social Landlords Discretionary Reduction of Service Charges (England) Direction 2014</em> allows social landlords to waive or reduce service charges by an amount that the landlord considers reasonable. For example, in cases of extreme hardship, the landlord may see fit to reduce charges to a leaseholder.</p>","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell",,"2017-04-20T13:16:45.75Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720286/answer","Biography information for Lord Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720286/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720286/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-04-13","Council Housing: Repairs and Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what steps his Department is taking to monitor the implementation of Florrie's Law.","false","Biography information for Neil Coyle","Bermondsey and Old Southwark","Neil Coyle","70452"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720287","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-04-25","<p>In 2012 we published ‘Challenge It, Report It Stop It’ which covered the period 2012-2014. This plan delivered real improvements in the way in which hate crime was reported. This was followed by the publication in July 2016 of ‘Action Against Hate’, the UK Government’s plan for tackling hate crime. In support of both action plans, the Department for Communities and Local Government has provided over £2.5 million to organisations during the period 2014-2017 to tackle hate crime.</p><p> </p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-04-25T14:25:13.92Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720287/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720287/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720287/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-04-13","Hate Crime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how much government funding has been provided to the hate crime programme in each year from 2014 to 2017.","false","Biography information for Lord Mann","Bassetlaw","John Mann","70433"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720288","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-04-25","<p>The Department of Communities and Local Government has contributed £90,000 towards the True Vision Programme during the period 2014 to 2017.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-04-25T14:31:21.217Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720288/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720288/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720288/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-04-13","Hate Crime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how much funding has been provided to the True Vision programme in each year from 2014 to 2017.","false","Biography information for Lord Mann","Bassetlaw","John Mann","70434"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720289","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-04-25","<p>True Vision is a facility owned by the National Police Chiefs' Council (NPCC) (and formerly by the Association of Chief Police Officers). Oversight of the scheme has been undertaken by the National Policing Lead, Assistant Chief Constable Mark Hamilton on behalf of National Police Chief’s Council. The manager of the scheme was temporarily accommodated by the Department for Communities and Local Government during an administrative transition from the Ministry of Justice to the Greater Manchester Police (on behalf of the National Police Chief's Council).</p><p> </p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-04-25T14:30:57.827Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720289/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720289/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720289/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-04-13","True Vision Programme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, for what reason responsibility for the True Vision programme was moved from the Ministry of Justice to his Department.","false","Biography information for Lord Mann","Bassetlaw","John Mann","70435"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720290","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-04-25","<p>Procurement spending on external consultants, including management consultants, for the period requested are published in the Department's annual report and accounts 2012 -13 to 2015-16. These can be found under the section “Expenditure on Consultancy and Temporary Staff” at the weblink below:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/dclg-annual-reports-and-accounts" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/dclg-annual-reports-and-accounts</a></p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-04-25T10:22:24.253Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720290/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720290/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720290/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-04-13","Department for Communities and Local Government: Management Consultants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, pursuant to the Answer of 7 March 2017 to Question 65679, on procurement, how much of the procurement spending in each of those years related to the services of management consultants.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","70248"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720291","Department for Transport","false","2017-04-21","<p>There is a general ban on pavement parking in London (except where expressly permitted). Outside London, Section 19 of the Road Traffic Act 1988 prohibits heavy goods vehicles from parking on the pavement. Other vehicles may park on the pavement unless the council choose to prohibit it by means of a Traffic Regulation Order under powers in the Road Traffic Regulation Act 1984. Yellow lines also apply to the pavement. Other options include the use of physical measures, such as high kerbs or bollards.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2017-04-21T11:33:37.113Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720291/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720291/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720291/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-04-13","Parking: Pedestrian Areas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what powers local authorities have to prevent vehicles parking on pavements.","false","Biography information for Richard Graham","Gloucester","Richard Graham","70232"
