"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720317","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-04-24","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer I gave on 31 March 2017 to Question 68970 to the hon. Member for Strangford (Mr Shannon).</p><p>http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2017-03-23/68970/</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2017-04-24T15:50:09.897Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720317/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720317/answer","20170331_68970_Armed_Forces_Communication.docx","70983 - WQnA extract on Armed Forces Communication","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720317/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-04-13","Armed Forces: Communication","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what assessment he has made of the effect of the cessation of the e-bluey system on the families of armed service personnel.","false","Biography information for Chris Elmore","Ogmore","Chris Elmore","70983"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720318","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-04-24","<p>The proposed move of No. 4 School of Technical Training from MOD St Athan to RAF Cosford will not directly affect the other units based there. However, as No. 4 School of Technical Training is the primary user of the support services at MOD St Athan, the scale of the support services provided at the site may be reviewed following the move.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2017-04-24T15:53:54.403Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720318/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720318/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720318/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-04-13","RAF St Athan","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what assessment he has made of the potential effect of relocation of No 4 School of Technical Training at St Athan to RAS Cosford on (a) 614 RAF Auxiliary Squadron, (b) University of Wales Air Squadron, (c) 2300 Air Cadets Squadron, (d) Regional Rehabilitation Unit for Wales and the Midlands and (e) the Band of the Prince of Wales; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mrs Madeleine Moon","Bridgend","Mrs Madeleine Moon","70832"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720319","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-04-24","<p>Membership of the Armed Forces’ Pay Review Body (AFPRB) is by Ministerial appointment. Applicants for public appointments go through a strict recruitment process which adheres to Cabinet Office policy and requirements set by the Office of the Commissioner for Public Appointments. Ministers are required to approve the recruitment programme, job advert and the composition of the Advisory Assessment Panel before the campaign begins. For AFPRB appointments the advisory panel consists of senior officials from the Ministry of Defence, Her Majesty’s Treasury, the Office of Manpower Economics as well as an independent member and, when appropriate, the Chair of the AFPRB. The role of the panel is to provide objective advice on appointable candidates who meet the published criteria for the job from which Ministers can select.</p><p> </p><p>During the last recruitment, which was advertised in August 2016, 37 applications were received.</p><p> </p><p>Currently the AFPRB consists of eight members, of which three are women. None are from a declared black or ethnic minority background or declared disabled. Information on whether members are from a lower socio-economic background is not requested and is therefore not held.</p><p> </p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster","70486 ; 70726","2017-04-24T15:58:11.72Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720319/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720319/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720319/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-04-13","Armed Forces' Pay Review Body: Public Appointments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, who makes appointments to the Board of the Armed Forces' Pay Review Body; which other organisations or individuals provide advice on those appointments; and at what stage of the process such advice is provided.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","70869"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720320","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-04-20","<p>The Armed Forces continue to have policies in place which require all allegations of sexual offences to be referred to the Service Police. Changes to Schedule 2 offences can be effected through secondary legislation, and the Department is looking for an early legislative opportunity to bring forward proposals for sexual assault, voyeurism and exposure to be included.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2017-04-20T15:08:08.003Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720320/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720320/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720320/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-04-13","Armed Forces: Sexual Offences","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, if he will set out the legislative timetable for making sexual assault, voyeurism and exposure schedule 2 offences under the Armed Forces Act 2006.","false","Biography information for Karl Turner","Kingston upon Hull East","Karl Turner","70904"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720321","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-04-24","<p>Ministry of Defence records are subject to the provisions of the Public Records Act 1958 (PRA) and there are no plans to change this policy.</p><p>In the last 30 years the rules have been changed to accord with relevant amendments to the PRA, such as the reduction of the retention period from 30 years to 20 years under the Constitutional Reform and Governance Act 2010.</p><p>Military service records are exempt from this policy on Data Protection Grounds. Service records are retained for a minimum of 100 years following an individual's date of birth.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2017-04-24T15:53:24.507Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720321/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720321/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720321/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-04-13","Ministry of Defence: Departmental Records","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, whether his Department has plans to change rules governing the disposal of military records; and whether any changes to those rules over the last 30 years.","false","Biography information for Chris Evans","Islwyn","Chris Evans","70694"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720322","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-04-24","<p>Membership of the Armed Forces’ Pay Review Body (AFPRB) is by Ministerial appointment. Applicants for public appointments go through a strict recruitment process which adheres to Cabinet Office policy and requirements set by the Office of the Commissioner for Public Appointments. Ministers are required to approve the recruitment programme, job advert and the composition of the Advisory Assessment Panel before the campaign begins. For AFPRB appointments the advisory panel consists of senior officials from the Ministry of Defence, Her Majesty’s Treasury, the Office of Manpower Economics as well as an independent member and, when appropriate, the Chair of the AFPRB. The role of the panel is to provide objective advice on appointable candidates who meet the published criteria for the job from which Ministers can select.</p><p> </p><p>During the last recruitment, which was advertised in August 2016, 37 applications were received.</p><p> </p><p>Currently the AFPRB consists of eight members, of which three are women. None are from a declared black or ethnic minority background or declared disabled. Information on whether members are from a lower socio-economic background is not requested and is therefore not held.</p><p> </p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster","70486 ; 70869","2017-04-24T15:58:11.83Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720322/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720322/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720322/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-04-13","Armed Forces' Pay Review Body: Public Appointments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what proportion of the Armed Forces' Pay Review Body board are (a) women, (b) from black or minority ethnic backgrounds, (c) disabled or (d) from lower socio-economic backgrounds.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","70726"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720323","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-04-24","<p>Discussions around the proposed relocation of No 4 School of Technical Training to RAF Cosford are ongoing and it would not be appropriate to publish these at this time.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2017-04-24T15:48:38.587Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720323/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720323/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720323/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-04-13","RAF St Athan","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, if he will place in the Library copies of discussion papers on the proposed relocation of his Department's St Athan No 4 School of Technical Training to RAF Cosford; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mrs Madeleine Moon","Bridgend","Mrs Madeleine Moon","70831"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720324","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-04-24","<p>The information requested is not held centrally and could be provided only at disproportionate costs.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2017-04-24T15:49:28.627Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720324/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720324/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720324/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-04-13","MOD Lyneham","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what the off-site accommodation costs for phase 3 trainees at RAF Lynham has been in each of the last five years; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mrs Madeleine Moon","Bridgend","Mrs Madeleine Moon","70758"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720325","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-04-24","<p>The sport and recreation facilities available at the MOD St Athan site consist of a Gym and an Astroturf pitch.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2017-04-24T15:57:18.237Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720325/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720325/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720325/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-04-13","RAF St Athan","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what sport and recreation facilities are available on his Department's St Athan site; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mrs Madeleine Moon","Bridgend","Mrs Madeleine Moon","70759"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720326","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-04-24","<p>The costs associated with the relocation of No. 4 School of Technical Training from MOD St Athan to RAF Cosford are still being finalised.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2017-04-24T15:50:46.357Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720326/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720326/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720326/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-04-13","RAF St Athan","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what estimate his Department has made of the costs of (a) staff relocation, (b) movement of equipment and (c) upgrading of buildings associated with transferring No. 4 School of Technical Training to Cosford; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mrs Madeleine Moon","Bridgend","Mrs Madeleine Moon","70761"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720327","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-04-24","<p>Work on the 2017 Initial Gate Business Case for Project CUBIT is ongoing and it would not be appropriate to publish it at this time.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2017-04-24T15:30:11.88Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720327/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720327/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720327/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-04-13","Ministry of Defence: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, if he will place the 2017 Initial Gate Business Case for Project CUBIT in the Library; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mrs Madeleine Moon","Bridgend","Mrs Madeleine Moon","70755"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720328","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-04-24","<p>During financial year 2016-17, the Ministry of Defence (MOD) accrued gross receipts of around £155 million, and released land with sufficient capacity for around 4,250 new homes.</p><p>Under the Better Defence Estate Strategy (A military led strategy), published on 7 November 2016, we are releasing 81 sites which will contribute towards the MOD's disposal and housing targets.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2017-04-24T15:27:01.597Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720328/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720328/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720328/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-04-13","Ministry of Defence: Land","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, with reference to paragraphs 1.296 and 1.297 of the Spending Review and Autumn Statement 2015, what progress his Department has made by estimated capacity of land sold since March 2016 in identifying and disposing of land to meet the Government's commitment.","false","Biography information for Mr Mark Prisk","Hertford and Stortford","Mr Mark Prisk","70674"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720329","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-04-24","<p>The Department will continue to explore a variety of options to augment the capabilities of the Queen Elizabeth Class aircraft carriers in future. Decisions on funding will be taken at the appropriate time within the Defence annual budget cycle.</p><p> </p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","70336 ; 70535","2017-04-24T15:39:23.283Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720329/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720329/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720329/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-04-13","Aircraft Carriers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, if he will examine options in SDSR 2020 to enable HMS Queen Elizabeth and HMS Prince of Wales to conduct long-range and rapid amphibious assault by air.","true","Biography information for James Heappey","Wells","James Heappey","70534"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720330","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-04-24","<p>The Department will continue to explore a variety of options to augment the capabilities of the Queen Elizabeth Class aircraft carriers in future. Decisions on funding will be taken at the appropriate time within the Defence annual budget cycle.</p><p> </p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","70336 ; 70534","2017-04-24T15:39:23.063Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720330/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720330/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720330/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-04-13","Aircraft Carriers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, if he will examine options in SDSR 2020 to enable HMS Queen Elizabeth and HMS Prince of Wales to extend the effective combat radius of the F-35B through the introduction of a shipborne air-to-air refuelling capability.","true","Biography information for James Heappey","Wells","James Heappey","70535"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720331","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-04-24","<p>The Department is currently developing plans for Maritime Intra Theatre Lift (MITL) based upon in-service helicopters. The Strategic Defence and Security Review 2020 process will consider the Defence requirement for a medium-to-long term MITL solution.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2017-04-24T15:40:03.193Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720331/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720331/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720331/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-04-13","Aircraft Carriers: Helicopters","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, when his Department plans for the Maritime Intra Theatre Lift Solution to be identified.","true","Biography information for James Heappey","Wells","James Heappey","70536"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720332","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-04-24","<p>The supply chain solution for the Queen Elizabeth Class aircraft carriers will vary according to the nature of the demand. The Department is currently developing plans for Maritime Intra Theatre Lift (MITL) based upon in-service helicopters.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2017-04-24T15:43:36.853Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720332/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720332/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720332/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-04-13","HMS Queen Elizabeth","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how his Department plans to supply the QEC Carrier Group at extended range with any critical items not held on board an accompanying solid support ship.","true","Biography information for James Heappey","Wells","James Heappey","70537"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720333","Department for International Development","false","2017-04-24","<p>The UK funds the delivery of life-saving medical services in Iraq, including in the Kurdistan Region. This support is delivered through a number of partners including the Iraq Humanitarian Pooled Fund and the International Organisation for Migration. Through our response to the conflict in Mosul we are helping to alleviate the pressure on the Kurdistan Region’s medical services.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2017-04-24T16:57:47.94Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720333/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720333/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720333/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-04-13","Iraq: Kurds","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what plans her Department has to make British medical aid available to the Kurdistan Region of Iraq.","false","Biography information for Dawn Butler","Brent Central","Dawn Butler","70506"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720334","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-04-24","<p>The costs of the planned Joint Intelligence Analysis Centre at RAF Croughton will be primarily funded by the United States, with some costs falling to the Ministry of Defence. However, as the Department will shortly be tendering for the works it would not be appropriate to release the costs as to do so would prejudice commercial interests.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2017-04-24T15:36:52.617Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720334/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720334/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720334/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-04-13","RAF Croughton","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what the cost (a) in total and (b) to the public purse will be of the planned development of the Joint Intelligence Operations Centre Europe Analytic Centre at RAF Croughton.","false","Biography information for Rachael Maskell","York Central","Rachael Maskell","70479"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720335","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-04-24","<p>Membership of the Armed Forces’ Pay Review Body (AFPRB) is by Ministerial appointment. Applicants for public appointments go through a strict recruitment process which adheres to Cabinet Office policy and requirements set by the Office of the Commissioner for Public Appointments. Ministers are required to approve the recruitment programme, job advert and the composition of the Advisory Assessment Panel before the campaign begins. For AFPRB appointments the advisory panel consists of senior officials from the Ministry of Defence, Her Majesty’s Treasury, the Office of Manpower Economics as well as an independent member and, when appropriate, the Chair of the AFPRB. The role of the panel is to provide objective advice on appointable candidates who meet the published criteria for the job from which Ministers can select.</p><p> </p><p>During the last recruitment, which was advertised in August 2016, 37 applications were received.</p><p> </p><p>Currently the AFPRB consists of eight members, of which three are women. None are from a declared black or ethnic minority background or declared disabled. Information on whether members are from a lower socio-economic background is not requested and is therefore not held.</p><p> </p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster","70726 ; 70869","2017-04-24T15:58:11.767Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720335/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720335/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720335/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-04-13","Armed Forces' Pay Review Body","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many applications the board of the Armed Forces' Pay Review Body received during its last intake.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","70486"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720336","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-04-20","<p>UK industry is making a significant contribution to the F-35 programme, providing 15% by value of every F-35 built. With regard to the Rolls-Royce lift fan system, approximately 70% of the development work and 40% of the production work is carried out in the UK. Given the nature of the supply chain, the Ministry of Defence does not hold further detailed information on the value of UK F-35 work that is specifically attributable to the lift fan.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","70606","2017-04-20T15:10:52.16Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720336/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720336/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720336/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-04-13","Joint Strike Fighter Aircraft","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what proportion of the value of the Joint Strike Fighter F-35B that is made in the UK is derived from the Rolls Royce lift fan; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mrs Madeleine Moon","Bridgend","Mrs Madeleine Moon","70605"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720337","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-04-20","<p>UK industry is making a significant contribution to the F-35 programme, providing 15% by value of every F-35 built. With regard to the Rolls-Royce lift fan system, approximately 70% of the development work and 40% of the production work is carried out in the UK. Given the nature of the supply chain, the Ministry of Defence does not hold further detailed information on the value of UK F-35 work that is specifically attributable to the lift fan.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","70605","2017-04-20T15:10:52.067Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720337/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720337/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720337/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-04-13","Joint Strike Fighter Aircraft","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what proportion of work on the Rolls Royce lift fan for the Joint Strike Fighter F-25B is carried out in the UK; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mrs Madeleine Moon","Bridgend","Mrs Madeleine Moon","70606"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720338","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-04-24","<p>As at 20 April 2017, 37,456 civilian staff were employed by Ministry of Defence. The number and proportion of civilian staff employed on:</p><p> </p><ul><li>full-time permanent contract is 32,530 (86.8%)</li><li>part-time permanent contract is 3,920 (10.5%)</li><li>a fixed-term contract of less than two years' duration (both full and part-time) is 300 (0.8%)</li><li>on an agency basis 706 (1.9%) (at 31 March 2017)</li></ul><p> </p><p>The Ministry of Defence does not employ individuals on zero hours contracts.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2017-04-24T15:45:44.9Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720338/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720338/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720338/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-04-13","Ministry of Defence: Conditions of Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many and what proportion of staff employed by his Department are employed on a contract which is (a) full-time permanent, (b) part-time permanent, (c) for less than two years' duration, (d) on an agency basis and (e) zero-hours.","false","Biography information for Rob Marris","Wolverhampton South West","Rob Marris","70460"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720339","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-04-24","<p>Junaid Hussain and Mohammed Emwazi were members of Daesh. The UK has been working as part of a Coalition since September 2014 which was invited by the Iraqi Prime Minister to defeat Daesh, on the legal basis of the collective self-defence of Iraq. This was confirmed by the UK Permanent Representative to the UN in a letter dated 25 November 2014 to the UN Secretary-General and the President of the Security Council indicating that the UK is taking measures &quot;to enable Iraqi forces to regain control of the borders of Iraq by striking ISIL [Daesh] sites and military strongholds in Syria&quot;.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2017-04-24T15:44:19.707Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720339/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720339/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720339/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-04-13","Syria: Military Intervention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, pursuant to the Answer of 24 February 2017 to Question 64013, on armed forces: deployment, what the legal basis was for UK involvement in US airstrikes against (a) Junaid Hussain and (b) Mohammed Emwazi.","false","Biography information for Kirsten Oswald","East Renfrewshire","Kirsten  Oswald","70393"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720340","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-04-24","<p>The information requested could be provided only at disproportionate cost. The security and stability of the UK has long depended on our strong partnerships in the Euro-Atlantic area, including NATO. Indeed, NATO remains the cornerstone of UK defence. Our European neighbours represent some of our closest friends and NATO allies, and our defence engagement with them reflects this as routine business. We exercise with them regularly to bolster our interoperability. For example, the Defence Secretary was in Tallinn last week for the opening ceremony of Estonia's NATO enhanced Forward Presence deployment, for which UK is framework nation.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2017-04-24T15:42:52.493Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720340/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720340/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720340/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-04-13","Armed Forces: Deployment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what deployments have been made of the armed forces to (a) other EU member states, (b) other non-EU EEA member states and (c) states which are applying for membership of the EU since 2010.","false","Biography information for Jeremy Lefroy","Stafford","Jeremy Lefroy","70366"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720341","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-04-24","<p>During financial year (FY) 2016-17, the Ministry of Defence (MOD) spent £103.4 million on Continuity of Education Allowance (CEA) for the children of Service personnel; this equates to £87.1 million for Service personnel assigned to the UK and £16.3 million for Service personnel assigned overseas. The earlier than usual processing of CEA claims for summer term 2017 has caused £23 million of expenditure to be accounted for in the last accounting period of FY 2016-17 rather than, as in previous years, the first accounting period of FY 2017-18. This accounting practice does not detract from the progress made since 2010 in reducing spend on this allowance.</p><p>The MOD also pays Boarding School Allowance and Day School Allowance towards schooling costs for the children of civilian employees who are posted overseas, with a small amount paid to officers who have returned to the UK but have continuing entitlement. In FY 2016-17 this amounted to £0.457 million, with £0.053 million paid to staff based in the UK and £0.404 million paid to staff based overseas.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2017-04-24T15:51:43.963Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720341/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720341/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720341/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-04-13","Ministry of Defence: Private Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how much was spent by his Department on private school fees for children of staff who are based (a) in the UK and (b) overseas in 2016-17.","false","Biography information for Rachel Reeves","Leeds West","Rachel Reeves","70381"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720342","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-04-24","<p>The Department will continue to explore a variety of options to augment the capabilities of the Queen Elizabeth Class aircraft carriers in future. Decisions on funding will be taken at the appropriate time within the Defence annual budget cycle.</p><p> </p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","70534 ; 70535","2017-04-24T15:39:23.127Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720342/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720342/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720342/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-04-13","Aircraft Carriers: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, with reference to paragraph 2.33 of the National Audit Office report, Delivering Carrier Strike, published on 16 March 2017, whether his Department plans to fund the Queen Elizabeth class carriers' logistic enablers in SDSR 2020.","true","Biography information for James Heappey","Wells","James Heappey","70336"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720343","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-04-24","<p>The Ministry of Defence is not enrolled on any trusted flagger programmes with social media companies.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2017-04-24T15:28:44.103Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720343/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720343/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720343/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-04-13","Ministry of Defence: Social Media","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, whether his Department is enrolled on any trusted flagger programmes with social media companies.","false","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Tom Watson","70275"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720344","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-04-24","<p>UK Armed Forces currently deployed to Iraq under Op SHADER are not involved with the detention or interrogation of any Iraqi prisoners. As such, there is no requirement for UK Armed Forces to make any video recordings of any interrogations of Iraqi detainees.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2017-04-24T15:44:56.017Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720344/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720344/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720344/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-04-13","Iraq: Detainees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, whether UK armed forces in Iraq have made official video recordings of interrogations of Iraqi detainees.","false","Biography information for Ann Clwyd","Cynon Valley","Ann Clwyd","70271"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720345","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-04-20","<p>Plans to commemorate the 100th anniversary of the RAF are well advanced. Events will take place across the UK throughout 2018 with the key event being a service taking place on 10 July 2018 at Westminster Abbey followed by a large flypast. Plans do not include the posthumous award of decorations for Service personnel.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2017-04-20T15:09:20.447Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720345/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720345/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720345/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-04-13","Air Force: Anniversaries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what plans are in place to commemorate the 100th anniversary of the RAF; and what discussions he has had with the RAF on the granting of posthumous awards for service personnel.","false","Biography information for Ian Murray","Edinburgh South","Ian Murray","70281"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720346","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-04-20","<p>There are no plans to use the 100th anniversary of the RAF to recognise Lady MacRobert's financial contribution to the RAF. The connection between the RAF and the MacRobert family is already maintained through the MacRobert Prize for graduating officers at RAF Cranwell. The Lady MacRobert Trophy is awarded between contesting Air Training Corps (ATC) squadrons in the North East Scotland Wing whilst 49F (Greenock (MacRobert's Reply)) Squadron of the ATC bears the family name.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2017-04-20T15:08:45.26Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720346/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720346/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720346/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-04-13","Air Force: Anniversaries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, whether there are plans in place to use the 100th anniversary of the RAF to commemorate the financial contribution made to the RAF by Lady MacRobert.","false","Biography information for Ian Murray","Edinburgh South","Ian Murray","70282"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720347","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-04-20","<p>The RAF does not routinely give individual aircraft names and there is no formal protocol or regulation regarding the naming of RAF aircraft. However, aircraft are occasionally given names and there is precedent, particularly during World War II, for philanthropic individuals or groups to donate aircraft and they were often given the opportunity to name them.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2017-04-20T15:10:02.297Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720347/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720347/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720347/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-04-13","Military Aircraft","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what procedures are in place for the naming of RAF aircraft.","false","Biography information for Ian Murray","Edinburgh South","Ian Murray","70279"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720348","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-04-24","<p>This information is not held in the format requested and could be provided only at disproportionate cost. I can, however, provide a breakdown of the Ministry of Defence’s total Net Expenditure on Advisory Consultancy since 2010. These figures represent expenditure on bringing in objective external advice on strategy, structure, management or operations outside the business-as-usual environment when in-house knowledge and experience are not available.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="6"><p>Advisory Consultancy Net Expenditure</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010-11</p></td><td><p>2011-12</p></td><td><p>2012-13</p></td><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>2014-15</p></td><td><p>2015-16</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>£25,780,990</p></td><td><p>£18,639,871</p></td><td><p>£44,611,000</p></td><td><p>£90,352,293</p></td><td><p>£91,234,749</p></td><td><p>£48,428,223</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2017-04-24T15:41:14.507Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720348/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720348/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720348/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-04-13","Ministry of Defence: Management Consultants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, pursuant to the Answer of 7 March 2017 to Question 65681, on procurement, how much of the procurement spending in each of those years related to the services of management consultants.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","70249"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720349","Department of Health","false","2017-04-24","<p>This information is not collected centrally.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2017-04-24T15:58:50.48Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720349/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720349/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720349/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-04-13","Veterans: Post-traumatic Stress Disorder","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many former service men and women were diagnosed with post-traumatic stress disorder in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Chris Evans","Islwyn","Chris Evans","70221"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720350","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-04-25","<p>The Government has committed to preventing and reducing homelessness for everyone, including armed forces veterans. That is why we have supported the Homelessness Reduction Bill, which will reform England’s homelessness legislation and ensure that more people get the help they need to prevent a homelessness crisis in the first place.</p><p>In addition, our £50 million Homelessness Prevention Programme has supported 84 projects across 205 district and unitary local authorities to deliver an end-to-end approach to prevention and rough sleeping.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-04-25T10:21:38.997Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720350/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720350/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720350/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-04-13","Veterans: Homelessness","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if he will estimate how many former service men and women were homeless in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Chris Evans","Islwyn","Chris Evans","70222"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720351","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-04-24","<p>The Department does not hold this information.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>However, in 2015/16 1000 former Servicemen and woman were receiving Armed Forces Independence Payment.</p><p> </p><p>The Information can be found in the following link - <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/603004/outturn-and-forecast-spring-budget-2017.ods" target="_blank">Outturn and forecast: Spring Budget 2017 (ODS)</a> Table 1c</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-04-24T11:40:56.78Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720351/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720351/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720351/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-04-13","Veterans: Personal Independence Payment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many former service men and women were in receipt of personal independence payments in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Chris Evans","Islwyn","Chris Evans","70223"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720352","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-04-25","<p>When claiming Jobseeker’s Allowance a person is only asked about their last job if it ended in the last 6 months. The data about their last job, if they had one, is recorded but could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>From April 2014 Individuals have also been asked by their Work Coach if they were formerly in HM Forces to ensure they are offered the most appropriate support. A marker recording their response is placed on their labour market account. The data available is not sufficiently robust to be published and will only provide a partial picture, as it is voluntarily provided information.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-04-25T11:45:37.393Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720352/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720352/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720352/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-04-13","Veterans: Jobseeker's Allowance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many former service men and women were in receipt of jobseeker’s allowance in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Chris Evans","Islwyn","Chris Evans","70224"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720353","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-04-24","<p>No records pertaining to the Haig Board of Inquiry into the Etaples mutiny of 1917 have been retained by the Ministry of Defence.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2017-04-24T15:58:59.047Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720353/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720353/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720353/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-04-13","World War I: Departmental Records","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, whether documents relevant to the Haig Board of Inquiry into the Etaples mutiny in 1917 are retained by the Government.","false","Biography information for Chris Evans","Islwyn","Chris Evans","70216"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720354","Department for Education","false","2017-04-20","<p>The Department’s annual expenditure includes the following amounts for spending on consultancy services:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Financial year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Spend on consultancy services</strong> <strong>£000</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2009-10</p></td><td><p>17,116</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010-11</p></td><td><p>36,707</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011-12</p></td><td><p>3,184</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012-13</p></td><td><p>985</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>840</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014-15</p></td><td><p>1,503</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015-16</p></td><td><p>1,208</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>The sources of the data are the department’s audited annual accounts covering the core department and its executive agencies at that time.</p><p> </p><p>The table includes the full cost of the consultants who have been engaged to implement changes or a new programme.</p><p> </p><p>The Department is only able to obtain information at the level in the table above; it does not hold the information requested in an appropriate format to say what proportion of that expenditure has been spent on management consultants.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-04-20T15:21:39.387Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720354/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720354/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720354/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-04-13","Department for Education: Management Consultants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the Answer of 30 March 2017 to Question 69291, on Department for Education: management consultants, for each of those years what the Department's spend has been in relation to the services of external experts engaged to implement the change or a new programme; and what proportion of that expenditure has been spent on management consultants.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","70284"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720355","Department for Education","false","2017-04-26","<p>The consultation 'Schools that Work for Everyone' set out our proposal to increase the number of selective schools, stating that at the same time we want to improve the educational outcomes for those who do not attend selective schools. The evidence on the performance of pupils in selective areas who are not in selective schools shows mixed results. Some studies find an association with slightly poorer average educational outcomes for these pupils[1], or only for those in areas with high proportions of selective places[2], whilst another study found no adverse effects for pupils in other schools[3]. The Government is considering the outcomes of the consultation and its intention is to publish its response in due course.</p><p> </p><p>[1] Atkinson, A., Gregg, P. and McConnell, B. (2004) The results of 11 Plus selection: an investigation into equity and efficiency of outcomes for pupils in selective LEAs, cited in Coe et al (2008) Evidence on the effects of selective educational systems, CEM Centre, Durham University for the Sutton Trust</p><p>[2] Andrews, J., Hutchinson, J., and Johnes, R. (2016) Grammar schools and social mobility. Education Policy Institute.</p><p>[3] Sutton Trust (2008) ‘Evidence on the effects of selective educational systems’ by the Centre for Evaluation and Monitoring, Durham University’</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-04-26T15:55:23.153Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720355/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720355/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720355/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-04-13","Schools: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, if she will make an assessment of the potential effect of expanding the number of selective schools on the performance of non-selective schools in that area.","false","Biography information for Catherine McKinnell","Newcastle upon Tyne North","Catherine McKinnell","70305"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720356","Department for Education","false","2017-04-24","<p>The Department does not collect data about the number of schools that are teaching creationism. Creationism does not accord with the scientific consensus or the very large body of established scientific evidence; nor does it accurately and consistently employ the scientific method. Outside of science lessons, there is scope for young people to discuss beliefs about the origins of the Earth and living things in religious education, providing that these discussions do not undermine the teaching of the established scientific consensus around evolution.</p><p> </p><p>The Government expects pupils in all state funded schools to study the nature of, and evidence for, evolution by the end of Key Stage 4. The Government’s expectations are set out in the National Curriculum, which maintained schools are required to follow, and in the funding agreements to which academies must adhere. The Department investigates complaints made about schools that are teaching creationism as a scientific theory contrary to the National Curriculum or their funding agreement.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-04-24T14:21:43.61Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720356/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720356/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720356/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-04-13","Creationism: Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what assessment she has made of the number of publicly funded schools that are teaching creationism.","false","Biography information for Ian Austin","Dudley North","Ian Austin","70286"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720357","Department for Education","false","2017-04-20","<p>Our rigorous processes are designed to ensure that only people who are capable of providing pupils with a good education are allowed to open new schools. We assess applications to establish free schools against published criteria and take into account a range of contextual information. As set out in <em>How to apply to set up a free school: guidance</em> published at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/opening-a-free-school" target="_blank"><em>https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/opening-a-free-school</em></a><em>, </em>the department carries out a range of checks on those proposing to set up and run free schools before and after they open. These include due diligence checks, credit checks and enhanced Disclosure and Barring Service checks and may include police and other checks necessary to ensure the suitability of people to be part of the free school programme. The results of these due diligence checks are taken into account when we make decisions about which applications to reject, but have not on their own led to a rejection decision.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2017-04-20T16:51:21.537Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720357/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720357/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720357/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-04-13","Free Schools","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many applications to open new free schools have been rejected on the grounds an individual applying has (a) been involved in illegal activities, (b) a criminal conviction and (c) been investigated or found guilty of misrepresentation, as per the Section 1 suitability and declaration form, in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Ian Austin","Dudley North","Ian Austin","70287"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720358","Department for Education","false","2017-04-24","<p>This is a matter for Her Majesty’s Chief Inspector, Amanda Spielman. I have asked her to write to you and a copy of her reply will be placed in the libraries of the House.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-04-24T14:27:58.133Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720358/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720358/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720358/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-04-13","Citizenship","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many schools have been found not to be teaching British values by Ofsted in each year since 2014.","false","Biography information for Ian Austin","Dudley North","Ian Austin","70288"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720359","Department for Education","false","2017-04-25","<p>For each financial year, the Department for Education publishes full audited accounts. These reports can be found at the link below:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/dfe-annual-reports" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/dfe-annual-reports</a></p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-04-25T15:45:01.477Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720359/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720359/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720359/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-04-13","Department for Education: Management Consultants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what estimate she has made of her Department's spending on procurement management in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","70335"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720360","Department for Education","false","2017-04-20","<p>Local authorities are responsible for making an assessment about the number of 30 hours free childcare places that providers plan to offer in their areas. To support them to deliver 30 hours, we are investing £100 million to create almost 18,000 additional early years places for eligible children to help meet demand from working parents. This is backed by £1 billion extra revenue per year for the early years entitlements, including £300 million per year to increase the funding rates paid to nurseries, pre-schools and childminders that choose to deliver the offer. This means that Wolverhampton local authority will see an increase in their hourly funding rate to £4.68.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-04-20T15:21:08.443Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720360/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720360/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720360/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-04-13","Nurseries: Wolverhampton North East","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what estimate she has made of the number of (a) nurseries and (b) nursery school places in Wolverhampton North East constituency that will offer 30 hours of free childcare from September 2017.","false","Biography information for Emma Reynolds","Wolverhampton North East","Emma Reynolds","70351"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720362","Department for Education","false","2017-04-20","<p>Supplementary funding for maintained nursery schools is allocated on a local authority basis, as is the free early years entitlements funding within the Dedicated Schools Grant. Of the £55m supplementary funding, the indicative allocation for Wolverhampton local authority is £1.04m in 2017-18.</p><p> </p><p>The supplementary funding will allow local authorities, including Wolverhampton, to maintain existing levels of nursery school funding. This extra funding will provide stability for nursery schools, which make a valuable contribution to improving the lives of some of our most disadvantaged children. We have recently completed a data assurance exercise that will ensure that local authorities receive the correct amount of supplementary funding.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-04-20T15:21:22.73Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720362/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720362/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720362/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-04-13","Nurseries: Wolverhampton","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, if she will estimate how much of the planned £55 million supplementary funding for maintained nurseries will be spent in (a) Wolverhampton and (b) Wolverhampton North East constituency; and what steps her Department is taking to support maintained nurseries in Wolverhampton.","false","Biography information for Emma Reynolds","Wolverhampton North East","Emma Reynolds","70352"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720363","Department for Education","false","2017-04-20","<p>The Department for Education does not collect specific data on family benefits or income; this would require analysis from the Department for Work and Pensions and Her Majesty’s Revenue and Customs.</p><p>1.4 million infants took a lunch on the January 2016 census day under the universal infant free school meals policy[1]. This is published and available at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/schools-pupils-and-their-characteristics-january-2016" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/schools-pupils-and-their-characteristics-january-2016</a>.</p><p>[1] National tables: SFR20/2016, table 3d. Number of Infant Pupils who took a lunch on census day (column E) minus Number of Infant Pupils Eligible for and claiming free school meals (column J)</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2017-04-20T16:48:55.893Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720363/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720363/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720363/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-04-13","Free School Meals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many children currently qualify for free school meals under (a) household benefit entitlement and (b) universal infant free school meals; and how many children living in households with an income of less than £16,190 are not eligible for free school meals because their parents are in receipt of working tax credit.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","70359"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720364","Department for Education","false","2017-04-20","<p>Funding for the free early years entitlements is allocated on a local authority basis. The early years funding allocation for Wolverhampton local authority can be found below for the following financial years:</p><p>2013-14:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/dedicated-schools-grant-2013-to-2014" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/dedicated-schools-grant-2013-to-2014</a></p><p>2014-15:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/dedicated-schools-grant-2014-to-2015" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/dedicated-schools-grant-2014-to-2015</a></p><p>2015-16:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/dedicated-schools-grant-dsg-2015-to-2016" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/dedicated-schools-grant-dsg-2015-to-2016</a></p><p>2016-17 (provisional allocation):</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/dedicated-schools-grant-dsg-2016-to-2017" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/dedicated-schools-grant-dsg-2016-to-2017</a></p><p>2017-18 (indicative allocation):</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/dedicated-schools-grant-dsg-2017-to-2018" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/dedicated-schools-grant-dsg-2017-to-2018</a></p><p> </p><p>Prior to 2013-14, early years local authority funding allocations were not separately identified within the Dedicated Schools Grant (DSG). Instead, they were part of the total DSG allocated to each local authority. Early years allocations prior to 2013-14 are not therefore available.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-04-20T15:21:57.327Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720364/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720364/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720364/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-04-13","Nurseries: Wolverhampton North East","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how much the Government has spent on nursery education in Wolverhampton North East constituency in each of the last seven years; and how much it plans to spend on such education in that constituency in the financial year 2017-18.","false","Biography information for Emma Reynolds","Wolverhampton North East","Emma Reynolds","70362"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720365","Department for Education","false","2017-04-20","<p>Local authorities are required to report annually to elected council members on how they are meeting their duty to secure sufficient childcare and early education places, and to make this report available and accessible to parents. The Department does not hold local authority or constituency level estimates of the number of places in local authority maintained nursery schools. However, the number of <em>pupils</em> attending local authority maintained nurseries can be found in the statistical first release and underlying data published at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/schools-pupils-and-their-characteristics-january-2016" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/schools-pupils-and-their-characteristics-january-2016</a></p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/445755/SFR16_2015_LA_tables.xlsx" target="_blank"><em>Local authority and regional tables: SFR20/2016 </em></a>(Table 7b) indicates that 686 pupils were registered as attending local authority maintained nursery schools in Wolverhampton in 2016.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-04-20T15:22:13.653Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720365/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720365/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720365/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-04-13","Nurseries: Wolverhampton North East","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what recent estimate she has made of the number of nursery school places in Wolverhampton North East constituency.","false","Biography information for Emma Reynolds","Wolverhampton North East","Emma Reynolds","70363"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720366","Department for Education","false","2017-04-27","<p>The Department recognises the value of international exchange and collaboration in education, as part of our vision for the UK as a global nation. There may be European programmes in which we might want to participate. We will consider this as part of the negotiation.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2017-04-27T08:16:36.54Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720366/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720366/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720366/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-04-13","Erasmus+ Programme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what representations she has made to her EU counterparts on the UK continuing to participate in the Erasmus programme after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Jeremy Lefroy","Stafford","Jeremy Lefroy","70364"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720367","Department for Education","false","2017-04-24","<p>The English Baccalaureate provides the right foundation for most pupils, and we want to see a significant increase in the proportion of pupils in mainstream secondary schools entering the English Baccalaureate subjects at GCSE.</p><p> </p><p>We are carefully considering the consultation responses and will publish the Government response in due course.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-04-24T14:15:40.047Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720367/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720367/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720367/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-04-13","English Baccalaureate: GCSE","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, when her Department plans to respond to its consultation on proposals to ensure that at least 90 per cent of pupils take GCSEs in EBacc subjects.","false","Biography information for Vicky Foxcroft","Lewisham, Deptford","Vicky Foxcroft","70376"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720368","Department for Education","false","2017-04-24","<p>We want schools to have the resources they need, and through our careful management of the economy we have been able to protect the core schools budget in real terms. School funding is now at its highest level on record at almost £41bn in 2017-18 - and that is set to rise, as pupil numbers rise, to £42 billion by 2019-20.</p><p> </p><p>We are going to end the historic post code lottery in school funding and under the proposed national schools funding formula, more than half of England’s schools will receive a cash boost.</p><p> </p><p>Our proposals include significant protections so that no school would face reductions of more than 1.5% per year or 3% overall per pupil as a result of this formula, and on high needs funding for pupils with special education needs and disabilities, no area would lose funding at all.</p><p> </p><p>We recognise the increasing cost pressures schools are facing and will continue to provide advice and support to help them use their funding in cost effective ways, and improve the way they buy goods and services, so‎ they get the best possible value for their pupils. We have produced tools, information and guidance for schools financial health and efficiency, which can be found at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/schools-financial-health-and-efficiency" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/schools-financial-health-and-efficiency</a>.</p><p> </p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-04-24T14:17:39.597Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720368/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720368/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720368/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-04-13","Pupils: Hartlepool","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, if she will make it her policy to increase the funding per pupil in Hartlepool constituency in real terms; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Iain Wright","Hartlepool","Mr Iain Wright","70383"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720369","Department for Education","false","2017-04-25","<p>The table below shows data on how many and what proportion of staff are employed by the Department for Education (DfE), on a contract which is full-time permanent and part-time permanent. The permanent headcount figures include staff who are on fixed-term contracts and have been employed for over 1 year but under 2 years. The fixed term/temporary figure shows staff on fixed-term contracts who have been employed for less than 1 year.</p><p>The total figure for (c) is therefore 212.</p><p> </p><p>Agency workers are not employees of DfE and have therefore not been included. DfE does not employ any staff on zero hours contracts.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Mar-17</p></td><td><p>DfE</p></td><td><p>GEO</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Paid headcount</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>4697</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>55</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>FT Permanent (a)</p></td><td><p>3941</p></td><td><p>44</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>PT Permanent (b)</p></td><td><p>660</p></td><td><p>10</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong><em>Of Permanent (c) </em></strong></p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p><em>FT contract (less than 2 years)</em></p></td><td><p><em>34</em></p></td><td><p><em>0</em></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><em>Other FT contract</em></p></td><td><p><em>109</em></p></td><td><p><em>0</em></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Fixed Term/Temporary (c)</p></td><td><p>69</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-04-25T15:49:22.057Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720369/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720369/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720369/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-04-13","Department for Education: Conditions of Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many and what proportion of staff employed by her Department are employed on a contract which is (a) full-time permanent, (b) part-time permanent, (c) for less than two years' duration, (d) on an agency basis and (e) zero-hours.","false","Biography information for Rob Marris","Wolverhampton South West","Rob Marris","70461"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720370","Department for Education","false","2017-04-24","<p>Cooking and nutrition are taught as part of the design and technology programme of study for Key Stage 1 to 3 in the National Curriculum. The National Curriculum is compulsory in maintained schools and can be used as a benchmark by academies and free schools.</p><p> </p><p>Within the programme of study, pupils are taught about food and nutrition and how to cook a range of healthy and nutritious meals. They are equipped with knowledge about healthy eating, what is meant by a balanced diet as well as how to feed themselves and others affordably and well.</p><p> </p><p>In September 2016, we also introduced a new GCSE in Food Preparation and Nutrition. The new GCSE enables pupils to acquire an understanding of the scientific principles behind food and nutrition, and use a number of practical cooking techniques to prepare and cook food. The first exam in this new qualification will be in summer 2018.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-04-24T14:19:50.193Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720370/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720370/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720370/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-04-13","Food Technology: Secondary Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what assessment she has made of the potential merits of making cookery a mandatory component of the secondary school curriculum.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","70410"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720371","Department for Education","false","2017-04-21","<p>The data requested for the 2016 calendar year will be published in the<em> ‘Statements of SEN and EHC plans: England: 2017’ </em>statistical first release on 25<sup>th</sup> May 2017.</p><p>Comparable data for the 2015 calendar year can be found in Table 2 of the<em> ‘Statements of SEN and EHC plans: England: 2016’ statistical first release: </em><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/statements-of-sen-and-ehc-plans-england-2016" target="_blank"><em>https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/statements-of-sen-and-ehc-plans-england-2016</em></a></p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2017-04-21T13:41:29.07Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720371/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720371/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720371/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-04-13","Special Educational Needs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many applications for education, health and care plans were (a) made, (b) accepted and (c) refused in 2016.","false","Biography information for Mr Barry Sheerman","Huddersfield","Mr Barry Sheerman","70416"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720372","Department for Education","false","2017-04-24","<p>At Key Stage 4, all pupils in maintained schools have an entitlement to study an arts subject and a design and technology subject.</p><p> </p><p>In addition to the revised curriculum introduced into schools in 2014, new GCSEs in a number of creative, artistic, and technical subjects including music, art and design, dance, drama, design and technology, food preparation and nutrition, electronics and engineering have been developed to be more rigorous.</p><p> </p><p>These GCSEs or any other GCSEs and technical awards from the Department approved list can count towards the open element of Progress and Attainment 8. These measures are designed to encourage schools to offer a broad and balanced curriculum.</p><p> </p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-04-24T14:14:24.133Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720372/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720372/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720372/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-04-13","GCSE","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps her Department is taking to encourage more students to take up a creative, artistic and technical subject at GCSE.","false","Biography information for Maggie Throup","Erewash","Maggie Throup","70427"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720373","Department for Education","false","2017-04-21","<p>The Department for Education (DfE) does not hold information on the number of teachers with responsibility for careers advice who have been trained in autism.</p><p>Since 2011 the DfE has funded the Autism Education Trust (AET) <a href="http://www.autismeducationtrust.org.uk" target="_blank">www.autismeducationtrust.org.uk</a> to deliver autism training at three levels to staff in early years, school and post-16 settings. Level 1 training is a basic 90-minute awareness session and Levels 2 and 3 are more in depth and aimed at staff who are working with autistic pupils on a daily basis. The AET has also developed a competency framework and standards for supporting pupils with autism.</p><p>To date, the AET has trained more than 130,000 people – not just teachers and teaching assistants, but also support staff such as receptionists, dining hall staff and caretakers.</p><p> </p>","Harlow","Robert Halfon",,"2017-04-21T11:53:10.18Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720373/answer","Biography information for Robert Halfon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720373/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720373/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-04-13","Schools: Vocational Guidance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many teachers with responsibility for providing careers advice have had training in autism.","false","Biography information for Caroline Ansell","Eastbourne","Caroline Ansell","70437"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720374","Department for Education","false","2017-04-20","<p>The Schools that Work for Everyone consultation outlined proposals for increasing the number of good school places available, including proposals to allow existing selective schools to expand and new selective schools to open. We proposed in the consultation that new and expanding schools should ensure that there are opportunities to join selective schools at different ages, such as 14 and 16, as well as 11. The consultation closed on 12 December. The government is considering the submissions received and will publish its response in due course.</p><p> </p><p>Good mental health and wellbeing are a priority for the Department. We have high aspirations for all children and want them to be able to fulfil their potential, both academically and in terms of their mental health. There is a lot that schools can do to prepare pupils well to take tests and exams, and to help parents support their children. Good teaching is one of the most important factors in making sure that pupils feel ready. Good leaders know that positive mental wellbeing supports attainment, and make that part of the overall school ethos.</p><p> </p><p>We want to look across the whole school system to identify where mental health provisions need to be improved, whether that is in schools or how we better connect schools into services that may be more specialised. We have supported schools by:</p><p> </p><ul><li>Funding the PSHE Association to publish guidance and a set of age –appropriate lesson plans on teaching about mental health issues;</li></ul><p> </p><ul><li>Publishing of a blueprint for school counselling services which provides schools with practical, evidence-based advice on how to deliver high quality school-based counselling to all pupils;</li></ul><p> </p><ul><li>Issuing advice on behaviour and mental health which provides teachers with information and tools that will help them to identify pupils who need help, provide effective early support and understand when a referral to a specialist mental health service may be necessary; and</li></ul><p> </p><ul><li>Funding the development of MindEd, a free online resource which allows all those working with children and young people to access information on a range of mental health issues.</li></ul><p> </p><p>The Prime Minister’s speech in January has further emphasised this Government’s commitment to improve mental health for all children and young people and announced that the Departments for Health and Education would publish a green paper on CYP’s mental health</p><p> </p><p>The Green Paper aims to secure effective activity from prevention to provision of specialist support, at different stages and different settings across health, education and care settings, as well as access to services, and the role of social media.</p><p> </p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson","70609 ; 70610","2017-04-20T16:48:10.873Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720374/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720374/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720374/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-04-13","Pupils: Mental Health","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what support is available for young people who suffer adverse effects to their mental health and well-being after not passing the 11-plus exam.","false","Biography information for Catherine McKinnell","Newcastle upon Tyne North","Catherine McKinnell","70608"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720375","Department for Education","false","2017-04-20","<p>The Schools that Work for Everyone consultation outlined proposals for increasing the number of good school places available, including proposals to allow existing selective schools to expand and new selective schools to open. We proposed in the consultation that new and expanding schools should ensure that there are opportunities to join selective schools at different ages, such as 14 and 16, as well as 11. The consultation closed on 12 December. The government is considering the submissions received and will publish its response in due course.</p><p> </p><p>Good mental health and wellbeing are a priority for the Department. We have high aspirations for all children and want them to be able to fulfil their potential, both academically and in terms of their mental health. There is a lot that schools can do to prepare pupils well to take tests and exams, and to help parents support their children. Good teaching is one of the most important factors in making sure that pupils feel ready. Good leaders know that positive mental wellbeing supports attainment, and make that part of the overall school ethos.</p><p> </p><p>We want to look across the whole school system to identify where mental health provisions need to be improved, whether that is in schools or how we better connect schools into services that may be more specialised. We have supported schools by:</p><p> </p><ul><li>Funding the PSHE Association to publish guidance and a set of age –appropriate lesson plans on teaching about mental health issues;</li></ul><p> </p><ul><li>Publishing of a blueprint for school counselling services which provides schools with practical, evidence-based advice on how to deliver high quality school-based counselling to all pupils;</li></ul><p> </p><ul><li>Issuing advice on behaviour and mental health which provides teachers with information and tools that will help them to identify pupils