"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720376","Department for Education","false","2017-04-27","<p>It has not proved possible to respond to the hon. Member in the time available before Prorogation.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-04-27T11:00:50.493Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720376/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720376/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720376/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-04-13","Teachers: Recruitment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how much her Department has spent on the Get into Teaching campaign in each year since its inception.","false","Biography information for Ian Austin","Dudley North","Ian Austin","70589"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720377","Department for Education","false","2017-04-21","<p>The current GCSE English and Maths requirements for early years educator (EYE) staff at level 3 have been broadened to include level 2 functional skills alongside other suitable qualifications. This is in response to the government consultation on the literacy and numeracy requirements for EYE staff and as part of the early years workforce strategy. The Skills Funding Agency will amend the apprenticeship funding rules, the Hub and the ILR validation rules so that anyone who started an early years apprenticeship on or after 1 September 2014 can now meet English and Maths requirements through the achievement of level 2 functional skills or other suitable qualifications.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p><strong><br> </strong></p><p> </p>","Harlow","Robert Halfon",,"2017-04-21T11:53:37.617Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720377/answer","Biography information for Robert Halfon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720377/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720377/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-04-13","Pre-school Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what discussions she has had with the Skills Funding Agency about allowing functional skills in English and mathematics to be permitted on the Early Years Educator Programme from April 2017.","false","Biography information for Michael Tomlinson","Mid Dorset and North Poole","Michael Tomlinson","70568"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720378","Department for Education","false","2017-04-24","<p>This is a matter for Ofqual, the Office of Qualifications and Examinations Regulation. I have asked its Chief Regulator, Sally Collier, to write directly to the Honourable Member. A copy of her reply will be placed in the House of Commons Library.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-04-24T13:56:10.633Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720378/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720378/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720378/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-04-13","GCE A-level","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the Answer of 29 March 2017 to Question 68556, what her policy is on the provision of resources and revision materials by exam boards for students taking reformed A-level courses.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","70481"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720379","Department for Education","false","2017-04-24","<p>In 2016/17 the school census was amended to collect additional pupil characteristic information. This included a question, for pupils whose language is recorded as anything other than English, as to their level of proficiency in English. The lowest level of proficiency which can be recorded is ‘New to English’.</p><p> </p><p>As stated in parliamentary question 62925 (9 February 2017)[1], it is our intention to publish information on the new data, including proficiency in English, nationality and country of birth, in the form of anonymised research within a statistical report. This will be made available later this year following completion of processing, analysis and assessment of data quality.</p><p><strong><br> </strong></p><p>[1] Found at <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2017-02-02/62925/" target="_blank">http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2017-02-02/62925/</a></p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-04-24T13:51:04.02Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720379/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720379/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720379/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-04-13","English Language: Southampton","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what proportion of pupils in Southampton are defined as New to English.","false","Biography information for Royston Smith","Southampton, Itchen","Royston Smith","70509"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720380","Department for Education","false","2017-04-24","<p>The Government is committed to ensuring equity of opportunity so that all pupils, irrespective of background, can fulfil their potential.</p><p>In the current system, whether a school receives any English as an additional language (EAL) funding, how long for, and how much they receive, all depends on the particular local funding formula.</p><p> </p><p>By contrast, under our proposals for a national funding formula, any qualifying pupil will be funded at the same rate. The EAL factor will include any pupil who entered the state education system in the last three years and is recorded on the census as having a first language other than English.</p><p>As in the current system, under a national funding formula, schools will continue to be responsible for deciding how to use their total funding allocation in order to support all their pupils.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","70511","2017-04-24T14:12:38.273Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720380/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720380/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720380/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-04-13","English Language: Pupils","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what (a) financial and (b) teaching support is offered to schools with significant numbers of pupils with English as an additional language.","false","Biography information for Royston Smith","Southampton, Itchen","Royston Smith","70510"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720381","Department for Education","false","2017-04-24","<p>The Government is committed to ensuring equity of opportunity so that all pupils, irrespective of background, can fulfil their potential.</p><p>In the current system, whether a school receives any English as an additional language (EAL) funding, how long for, and how much they receive, all depends on the particular local funding formula.</p><p> </p><p>By contrast, under our proposals for a national funding formula, any qualifying pupil will be funded at the same rate. The EAL factor will include any pupil who entered the state education system in the last three years and is recorded on the census as having a first language other than English.</p><p>As in the current system, under a national funding formula, schools will continue to be responsible for deciding how to use their total funding allocation in order to support all their pupils.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","70510","2017-04-24T14:12:38.32Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720381/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720381/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720381/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-04-13","English Language: Pupils","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what (a) financial and (b) teaching support is offered to schools with significant numbers of New to English pupils.","false","Biography information for Royston Smith","Southampton, Itchen","Royston Smith","70511"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720382","Department for Education","false","2017-04-24","<p>This is a matter for Her Majesty’s Chief Inspector, Amanda Spielman. I have asked her to write to you and a copy of her reply will be placed in the libraries of the House.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-04-24T13:52:05.703Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720382/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720382/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720382/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-04-13","English Language: Pupils","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how the Ofsted assessment of schools recognises schools with a large New to English population.","false","Biography information for Royston Smith","Southampton, Itchen","Royston Smith","70512"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720383","Department for Education","false","2017-04-24","<p>The appointing Departments – Department for Education, Department for Work and Pensions, and Cabinet Office – received 98 applications for the position of Commission Member for the Social Mobility Commission during the last recruitment process.</p><p>The Board of the Social Mobility Commission comprises the Rt Hon Alan Milburn as Chair, the Rt Hon Baroness Gillian Shephard as Deputy Chair and two other commissioners, Paul Gregg and David Johnston. We do not hold detailed profiling information on Commission members, however you can find their biographies on the Social Mobility Commission webpage at this link:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/organisations/social-mobility-commission" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/organisations/social-mobility-commission</a></p><p>All members of the Commission are appointed by a Minister of the Crown and the positions are regulated by the Commissioner for Public Appointments. All appointments are undertaken in line with the Governance Code on Public Appointments, which you can find at the following link: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/578498/governance_code_on_public_appointments_16_12_2016.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/578498/governance_code_on_public_appointments_16_12_2016.pdf</a></p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","70721 ; 70865","2017-04-24T14:59:12.087Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720383/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720383/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720383/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-04-13","Social Mobility Commission","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many applications the board of the Social Mobility Commission received during its last intake.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","70495"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720384","Department for Education","false","2017-04-21","<p>Criterion defining which organisations will pay the levy is published on gov.uk: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/apprenticeship-levy-how-it-will-work" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/apprenticeship-levy-how-it-will-work</a> Organisations will first declare that they will pay the levy in May 2017.</p><p> </p><p>As stated in the reply of 30 March to my Hon. Friend’s PQ 69076, both levy and non-levy paying employers can access funding towards the cost of an apprentice’s training and assessment. Levy paying employers will have funds available to them through the apprenticeship service and receive a 10% Government top up every month. Non-levy paying employers will contribute 10% towards the cost of training with the Government paying 90%.</p><p> </p><p>As individual employers, Hon. Members and members of the House of Lords will be able to check their eligibility for funding the training of apprentices they hire. The Apprenticeship Funding Rules are available at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/sfa-funding-rules-2016-to-2017" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/sfa-funding-rules-2016-to-2017</a></p>","Harlow","Robert Halfon","70503","2017-04-21T11:54:19.747Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720384/answer","Biography information for Robert Halfon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720384/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720384/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-04-13","Apprentices: Members' Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, whether hon. Members are able to access (a) funding for apprenticeships and (b) apprentices on account of the House's contribution to the apprenticeship levy; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Karin Smyth","Bristol South","Karin Smyth","70502"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720385","Department for Education","false","2017-04-21","<p>Criterion defining which organisations will pay the levy is published on gov.uk: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/apprenticeship-levy-how-it-will-work" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/apprenticeship-levy-how-it-will-work</a> Organisations will first declare that they will pay the levy in May 2017.</p><p> </p><p>As stated in the reply of 30 March to my Hon. Friend’s PQ 69076, both levy and non-levy paying employers can access funding towards the cost of an apprentice’s training and assessment. Levy paying employers will have funds available to them through the apprenticeship service and receive a 10% Government top up every month. Non-levy paying employers will contribute 10% towards the cost of training with the Government paying 90%.</p><p> </p><p>As individual employers, Hon. Members and members of the House of Lords will be able to check their eligibility for funding the training of apprentices they hire. The Apprenticeship Funding Rules are available at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/sfa-funding-rules-2016-to-2017" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/sfa-funding-rules-2016-to-2017</a></p>","Harlow","Robert Halfon","70502","2017-04-21T11:54:19.683Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720385/answer","Biography information for Robert Halfon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720385/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720385/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-04-13","Apprentices: Parliament","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, with reference to the combined salary bill of hon. members and Members of the House of Lords being in excess of the threshold for payment of the apprenticeship levy, if she will take steps to facilitate parliamentarians in contributing to and accessing funding for apprenticeships both in Parliament and in their parliamentary constituencies; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Karin Smyth","Bristol South","Karin Smyth","70503"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720386","Department for Education","false","2017-04-24","<p>There are no plans to review survivors’ benefits from the Teachers’ Pension Scheme. It has been the policy of successive Governments that any changes or improvements to public service pension schemes are not normally applied retrospectively. This policy protects the current membership and taxpayers from having to meet unforeseen additional costs that were not previously taken into account, and to which those who would benefit have not contributed towards.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-04-24T13:57:42.713Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720386/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720386/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720386/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-04-13","Teachers: Pension Rights","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what plans she has to equalise survivors' benefits from the Teachers' Pension Scheme for widowers, civil partners and same sex married couples with those for widows.","false","Biography information for Jeremy Lefroy","Stafford","Jeremy Lefroy","70515"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720387","Department for Education","false","2017-04-25","<p>The Department completed its sale of planned surplus properties in 2015-2016 and therefore there has been no sale of surplus property assets from the core departmental estate in 2016-17.</p><p>The Department keeps its estate under review to ensure that it delivers value for money.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-04-25T15:58:01.427Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720387/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720387/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720387/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-04-13","Department for Education: Land","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, with reference to paragraphs 1.296 and 1.297 of the Spending Review and Autumn Statement 2015, what progress her Department has made by estimated capacity of land sold since March 2016 in identifying and disposing of land to meet the Government's commitment.","false","Biography information for Mr Mark Prisk","Hertford and Stortford","Mr Mark Prisk","70675"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720388","Department for Education","false","2017-04-21","<p>The Apprenticeship Levy came into effect on 6 April 2017 and will enable us to fund the step change needed to achieve 3 million quality apprenticeship starts in England by 2020. Delivering better quality apprenticeships will ensure that more people from all backgrounds are enabled to gain the skills and training they need to build successful careers.</p><p>The apprenticeships programme is demand led, and employers will recruit apprentices that are appropriate for their business needs. The new funding model will support training for individuals from disadvantaged areas, by providing a cash payment to providers for training apprentices who live in the top 27% of deprived areas. This will be in place for a year, and we will continue to review our approach to funding apprenticeships for the most disadvantaged.</p><p>We are investing in skills across the whole of England: by 2019-20 our annual spending on apprenticeships in England will reach £2.45bn – double in cash terms what is was in 2010-11. Apprenticeships budget from 2016-2020 can be found on page 8 at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/545145/Apprenticeships_-expected_levy_and_total_spend_-_Aug_2016.pdf" target="_blank">Information on apprenticeship levy</a>.</p><p> </p><p>Apprenticeships are a devolved policy. The Devolved Administrations will each receive their fair share of the apprenticeship levy increasing to £460 million by 2019-20. It will be for them to decide how funds raised from the levy should be used in their administrations.</p>","Harlow","Robert Halfon","70625 ; 70846","2017-04-21T09:57:04.087Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720388/answer","Biography information for Robert Halfon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720388/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720388/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-04-13","Apprentices: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, if she will ensure that investment from the apprenticeship levy benefits less affluent areas the most.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","70626"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720389","Department for Education","false","2017-04-20","<p>The following table shows the estimated number of secondary school teachers in England, November 2010 to 2015, teaching (a) music, (b) drama and (c) art and design.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Music</p></td><td><p>Drama</p></td><td><p>Art and Design</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010</p></td><td><p>7,500</p></td><td><p>11,100</p></td><td><p>13,200</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011</p></td><td><p>8,000</p></td><td><p>11,600</p></td><td><p>13,900</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>7,400</p></td><td><p>10,500</p></td><td><p>12,800</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>7,300</p></td><td><p>10,200</p></td><td><p>12,700</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>7,100</p></td><td><p>9,600</p></td><td><p>12,400</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>6,900</p></td><td><p>9,400</p></td><td><p>12,000</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>Source: School Workforce Census</p><p>The number of teachers teaching each subject in secondary schools are estimates. The annual School Workforce Census typically receives curriculum taught data for over 70% of secondary school teachers. The sample data received have been weighted and grossed so that all figures presented provide a representative, national picture. Due to the sample nature of the data received, regional and local estimates are not produced.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-04-20T15:57:41.773Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720389/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720389/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720389/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-04-13","Arts: Teachers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many (a) music, (b) drama and (c) art teachers there were in each region of England in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Tom Watson","70790"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720390","Department for Education","false","2017-04-21","<p>We are delivering all of the recommendations made by the Maynard taskforce and expect to have fully implemented them by April 2018. The recommendations focused on a range of disabilities, including autism. We expect the actions taken to improve access to and completion of apprenticeships for a broad range of people with learning difficulties and disabilities, including those with autism.</p><p> </p><p>Alongside our work to implement the recommendations of the taskforce, in March 2017 we announced a new disability success measure to increase the proportion of apprenticeships starts by people with learning difficulties and disabilities by 20% by 2020 in our Apprenticeship Reform Programme: Benefits Realisation document. Whilst we have not limited success measures for specific groups with learning difficulties and disabilities, for example, individuals with autism, we expect our work on implementing the recommendations and working towards achieving our success measures to have an impact on a broad range of people with different learning difficulties and disabilities.</p><p> </p><p>Data is not collected in such a way as to be able to identify apprentices with autism. Achievements for those apprentices that have declared a learning difficulty or disability for the 2013/14 and 2014/15 academic years can be found here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/504335/apprenticeships-achievements-by-geography-learner-demographics-and-sector-subject-area.xls" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/504335/apprenticeships-achievements-by-geography-learner-demographics-and-sector-subject-area.xls</a>. Data for the 2015/16 academic year will be published in due course.</p>","Harlow","Robert Halfon","70769 ; 70771","2017-04-21T11:53:27.07Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720390/answer","Biography information for Robert Halfon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720390/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720390/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-04-13","Apprentices: Autism","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, if she will take steps to monitor the effect of the work of the Apprenticeships Taskforce on autism employment.","false","Biography information for Michael Tomlinson","Mid Dorset and North Poole","Michael Tomlinson","70770"
