"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720403","Department for Education","false","2017-04-24","<p>The appointing Departments – Department for Education, Department for Work and Pensions, and Cabinet Office – received 98 applications for the position of Commission Member for the Social Mobility Commission during the last recruitment process.</p><p>The Board of the Social Mobility Commission comprises the Rt Hon Alan Milburn as Chair, the Rt Hon Baroness Gillian Shephard as Deputy Chair and two other commissioners, Paul Gregg and David Johnston. We do not hold detailed profiling information on Commission members, however you can find their biographies on the Social Mobility Commission webpage at this link:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/organisations/social-mobility-commission" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/organisations/social-mobility-commission</a></p><p>All members of the Commission are appointed by a Minister of the Crown and the positions are regulated by the Commissioner for Public Appointments. All appointments are undertaken in line with the Governance Code on Public Appointments, which you can find at the following link: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/578498/governance_code_on_public_appointments_16_12_2016.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/578498/governance_code_on_public_appointments_16_12_2016.pdf</a></p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","70495 ; 70865","2017-04-24T14:59:12.137Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720403/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720403/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720403/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-04-13","Social Mobility Commission","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what proportion of the Social Mobility Commission board are (a) women, (b) from black or minority ethnic backgrounds, (c) disabled or (d) from lower socio-economic backgrounds.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","70721"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720404","Department for Education","false","2017-04-24","<p>Local authorities are responsible for ensuring there are sufficient school places for pupils. The Department collects pupil number forecasts and school capacity data from each local authority through the annual school capacity survey (SCAP). This data is used to allocate capital funding to local authorities to help them provide sufficient school places where they are needed. The Department’s Pupil Place Planning team then work with the Local Authorities to determine those places that are in fact being created.</p><p> </p><p>The capacity and forecasts data are published on an annual basis, giving local authority and regional totals, through the SCAP tables which can be found at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/statistics-school-capacity" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/statistics-school-capacity</a>. School capacity and forecast data is not available at constituency level.</p><p> </p><p>The following table provides the requested information on available school places (school capacity) in Kirklees and England in each year from 2009/10 to 2015/16.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Table 1: School capacity in state funded primary and secondary schools</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p><strong>2009/10</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2010/11</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2011/12</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2012/13</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2013/14</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2014/15</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2015/16</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>England</p></td><td><p>7,790,645</p></td><td><p>7,862,272</p></td><td><p>7,914,563</p></td><td><p>8,053,509</p></td><td><p>8,239,830</p></td><td><p>8,389,479</p></td><td><p>8,525,736</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Kirklees</p></td><td><p>65,493</p></td><td><p>65,739</p></td><td><p>66,575</p></td><td><p>66,849</p></td><td><p>67,567</p></td><td><p>67,996</p></td><td><p>68,506</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>School capacities are as reported by local authorities for all school types, based on their knowledge of each school.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-04-24T14:56:57.697Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720404/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720404/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720404/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-04-13","Schools: Admissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many school places have been available in (a) Batley and Spen constituency, (b) Kirklees and (c) England in each of the last seven years.","false","Biography information for Tracy Brabin","Batley and Spen","Tracy Brabin","70917"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720405","Department for Education","false","2017-04-24","<p>The Priority School Building Programme (PSBP) is spending £4.4 billion on rebuilding or refurbishing those buildings in the worst condition at 537 schools across England.</p><p>The investment is being targeted more effectively than before, with investment decisions based on a comprehensive picture of the needs of the school estate. In doing so we are maximising the impact of every pound of taxpayers’ money.</p><p>Under PSBP, timescales to start building works have been cut by up to two years and the average cost is a third less than under Building Schools for the Future (BSF).</p><p>All schools, including those that were due for rebuilding under BSF, were invited to apply to the PSBP. Successful schools were prioritised for the programme based on their condition need.</p><p>The vast majority of schools within the first phase of the programme will be delivered by the end of 2017, two years earlier than originally planned.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-04-24T14:46:56.87Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720405/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720405/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720405/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-04-13","Priority School Building Programme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, whether she plans to rebuild schools which were due for rebuilding under the Building Schools for the Future programme as part of the Priority Schools Building programme.","false","Biography information for Rachael Maskell","York Central","Rachael Maskell","70915"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720406","Department for Education","false","2017-04-26","<p>Building Schools for the Future was cancelled in July 2010. Rather than providing new school places, the programme’s main aim was to rebuild or refurbish all secondary and special schools in England by 2020.</p><p>Supporting local authorities to create sufficient school places is one of the Government’s top priorities and we fund all school places needed based on local authorities’ own forecasts. We are spending £7 billion to create new school places between 2015 and 2021, which, along with our investment in the free schools programme, we expect to provide 600,000 new places, including 270,000 in free schools. The latest data shows that nearly 735,000 additional pupil places were created between May 2010 and May 2016 with many more delivered since then and in the pipeline.</p><p>On top of this, our current school rebuilding programme, the Priority School Building Programme, is meeting the condition need at 537 schools across the country. It has reduced timescales to start building works by up to two years and is delivering projects for a third cheaper than Building Schools for the Future.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-04-26T15:53:43.173Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720406/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720406/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720406/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-04-13","Building Schools for the Future Programme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what assessment she has made of the effect of the decision to end the Building Schools for the Future programme on the number of available school places.","false","Biography information for Tracy Brabin","Batley and Spen","Tracy Brabin","70916"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720407","Department for Education","false","2017-04-26","<p>We are committed to introducing a national funding formula for schools that will calculate schools’ funding allocations consistently and transparently, using an up to date assessment of need. We believe this represents a fairer way of funding schools.</p><p> </p><p>We have consulted on our proposals and we are grateful to those who have taken the time to highlight their views as part of this process. We received over 25,000 responses to the consultation, which we are reviewing in detail.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-04-26T15:33:53.4Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720407/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720407/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720407/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-04-13","Schools: West Yorkshire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what recent discussions she has had with headteachers in (a) Batley and Spen constituency and (b) Kirklees on (i) school funding and (ii) the effect of the new school funding formula on schools in those areas.","false","Biography information for Tracy Brabin","Batley and Spen","Tracy Brabin","70912"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720408","Department for Education","false","2017-04-24","<p>The appointing Departments – Department for Education, Department for Work and Pensions, and Cabinet Office – received 98 applications for the position of Commission Member for the Social Mobility Commission during the last recruitment process.</p><p>The Board of the Social Mobility Commission comprises the Rt Hon Alan Milburn as Chair, the Rt Hon Baroness Gillian Shephard as Deputy Chair and two other commissioners, Paul Gregg and David Johnston. We do not hold detailed profiling information on Commission members, however you can find their biographies on the Social Mobility Commission webpage at this link:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/organisations/social-mobility-commission" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/organisations/social-mobility-commission</a></p><p>All members of the Commission are appointed by a Minister of the Crown and the positions are regulated by the Commissioner for Public Appointments. All appointments are undertaken in line with the Governance Code on Public Appointments, which you can find at the following link: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/578498/governance_code_on_public_appointments_16_12_2016.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/578498/governance_code_on_public_appointments_16_12_2016.pdf</a></p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","70495 ; 70721","2017-04-24T14:59:12.197Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720408/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720408/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720408/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-04-13","Social Mobility Commission: Public Appointments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, who makes appointments to the Board of the Social Mobility Commission; which other organisations or individuals provide advice on those appointments; and at what stage of the process such advice is provided.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","70865"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720409","Department for Education","false","2017-04-21","<p>The Apprenticeship Levy came into effect on 6 April 2017 and will enable us to fund the step change needed to achieve 3 million quality apprenticeship starts in England by 2020. Delivering better quality apprenticeships will ensure that more people from all backgrounds are enabled to gain the skills and training they need to build successful careers.</p><p>The apprenticeships programme is demand led, and employers will recruit apprentices that are appropriate for their business needs. The new funding model will support training for individuals from disadvantaged areas, by providing a cash payment to providers for training apprentices who live in the top 27% of deprived areas. This will be in place for a year, and we will continue to review our approach to funding apprenticeships for the most disadvantaged.</p><p>We are investing in skills across the whole of England: by 2019-20 our annual spending on apprenticeships in England will reach £2.45bn – double in cash terms what is was in 2010-11. Apprenticeships budget from 2016-2020 can be found on page 8 at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/545145/Apprenticeships_-expected_levy_and_total_spend_-_Aug_2016.pdf" target="_blank">Information on apprenticeship levy</a>.</p><p> </p><p>Apprenticeships are a devolved policy. The Devolved Administrations will each receive their fair share of the apprenticeship levy increasing to £460 million by 2019-20. It will be for them to decide how funds raised from the levy should be used in their administrations.</p>","Harlow","Robert Halfon","70625 ; 70626","2017-04-21T09:57:04.21Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720409/answer","Biography information for Robert Halfon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720409/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720409/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-04-13","Apprentices: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what provisions have been put in place to ensure that the apprenticeship levy is equally beneficial to all areas of the UK.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","70846"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720410","Department for Education","false","2017-04-21","<p>The Department does not hold data on absence due to children's dental problems. Figures for absence by reason, including authorised absence for illness and medical/dental appointments, are published in “Pupil absence in schools in England: 2015 to 2016”, available at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/pupil-absence-in-schools-in-england-2015-to-2016" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/pupil-absence-in-schools-in-england-2015-to-2016</a></p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2017-04-21T13:43:03.767Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720410/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720410/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720410/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-04-13","Pupils: Dental Health","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what estimate her Department has made of the number of school days lost as a result of children's dental problems in each of the last five school years.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","70857"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720411","Department for Education","false","2017-04-25","<p>The Department has no central record of staff seconded to it from other organisations or companies. Therefore, it is not possible to verify how many or from which organisations staff may have been seconded. This is because secondments are agreed by individual managers and may not always be notified to the central Human Resources team.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-04-25T15:47:02.047Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720411/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720411/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720411/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-04-13","Department for Education: Secondment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many staff are seconded to her Department; and how many such staff are seconded from which companies and organisations.","false","Biography information for Tracy Brabin","Batley and Spen","Tracy Brabin","70946"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720412","Department for Education","false","2017-04-20","<p>Information on the number of free schools in temporary accommodation in London and England can be found below:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Total free schools in London in temporary accommodation</p></td><td><p>54</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Total free schools in England in temporary accommodation</p></td><td><p>110</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Total free schools in London in temporary accommodation for more than 1 year</p></td><td><p>41</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Total free schools in England in temporary accommodation for more than 1 year</p></td><td><p>74</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>The length of time it takes to identify, acquire and adapt the right site can mean that it is sometimes necessary for a school to open in temporary accommodation. When we do open schools in temporary accommodation, we ensure value for money and that all temporary accommodation is safe and suitable for educational purposes.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-04-20T15:53:14.76Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720412/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720412/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720412/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-04-13","Free Schools","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many free schools in (a) London and (b) England are in temporary buildings; and how many of those schools have been in those temporary buildings for more than one year.","false","Biography information for Mr Steve Reed","Croydon North","Mr Steve Reed","70992"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720413","Department for Education","false","2017-04-20","<p>We do not currently hold this information across the whole school estate.</p><p>The Condition Data Collection (CDC) programme will help us to identify this information in the future.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-04-20T15:54:09.77Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720413/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720413/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720413/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-04-13","Schools: Buildings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many schools are in temporary buildings in (a) England and (b) each local authority area.","false","Biography information for Mr Steve Reed","Croydon North","Mr Steve Reed","70993"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720414","Department for Education","false","2017-04-24","<p>We are taking wide-ranging action to address the issues raised by the Joseph Rowntree Foundation report and ensure that all children are provided with an excellent education.</p><p> </p><p>In the <em>Schools that work for everyone</em> consultation we signalled our intention to build a diverse education system in which all children can receive a high-quality education that is right for them, regardless of their background or postcode. We are seeking to overturn the ban on new selective schools to ensure that the best and brightest students can enjoy a stretching curriculum, implementing this reform in a way that places conditions on grammar schools, as well as independent schools and universities, to ensure that they do more to raise standards across the whole system.</p><p> </p><p>Working with head teachers and other sector experts we have reformed the National Professional Qualifications to better prepare leaders for the range of roles in today’s school system and have funded the High Potential Middle Leaders and High Potential Senior Leaders programmes to develop excellent leaders in challenging schools. An independent expert group convened by the department has defined a new standard for teachers’ professional development and we have announced plans to invest around £75 million in the Teaching and Leadership Innovation Fund over the next three years to support high-quality professional development for teachers and school leaders in the areas of the country and schools that need it most.</p><p> </p><p>Our £137 million investment in the Education Endowment Foundation (EEF) is expanding the evidence base on what works to raise the attainment of disadvantaged pupils. As part of its dissemination activity the EEF, in partnership with the Institute for Effective Education, has established a network of Research Schools to support the use of evidence in improving teaching practice.</p><p> </p><p>Reforms brought in by the Children and Families Act 2014 are transforming the support available to children and young people with SEN and disabilities (SEND) by joining up services for 0-25 year olds across education, health and social care and by focusing on positive outcomes for education, employment, housing, health and community participation. Building on effective practice to support disadvantaged pupils we have funded the development of the SEND Review, based on the model of the Pupil Premium Review, to support SEND focussed school-to-school improvement. Since 2015, we have funded the Whole School SEND consortium to embed the SEND review nationally and encourage school leaders to give greater priority to improving their SEND provision.</p><p> </p><p>Schools have a clear legal duty not to discriminate against pupils under the Equality Act 2010. Statutory guidance on exclusions is clear that head teachers should make additional efforts to consider what extra support is needed to avoid exclusion for groups with disproportionately high rates of exclusion, including those with SEND and pupils from Gypsy Roma Traveller communities. Our plans to reform the use of alternative provision (AP) include making schools accountable for the ongoing education and outcomes of pupils who require AP, such as those who are permanently excluded. This will further strengthen incentives for schools to take earlier action where problems emerge that put pupils at risk of exclusion.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2017-04-24T14:32:48.963Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720414/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720414/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720414/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-04-13","Children: Poverty","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, with reference to page 123 of the report, UK Poverty: Causes and Solutions, published by the Joseph Rowntree Foundation on 6 September 2016, if she will make an assessment of the potential merits of implementing the recommendations in that report on providing all children with an excellent education.","false","Biography information for Lyn Brown","West Ham","Lyn Brown","70976"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720415","Department for Education","false","2017-04-27","<p>Following the reforms to the funding system in 2012, real progress continues to be made in widening participation in higher education. The proportion of young people from disadvantaged backgrounds going into higher education has risen from 13.6% in 2009 to 19.5% in 2016.</p><p>As a result of the funding changes and the increased income available to universities, with universities forecasting income growth of £2.3bn by 2020 from their planned expansion of student places, there is an expectation that HE providers should take more responsibility for widening participation.</p><p>Through access agreements universities expect to spend £833.5 million in 2017/18 on measures to improve access and success for students from disadvantaged backgrounds. This is up significantly from £404 million in 2009.</p><p>Subject to the passage of the Higher Education and Research Bill we are further strengthening our approach to widening participation by:</p><p> </p><p>o Establishing the Office for Students (OfS), which will have a statutory duty to consider the promotion of equality of opportunity in relation to access and participation.</p><p>o Introducing a Transparency Duty requiring providers to publish application, offer, drop-out and attainment rates of students broken down by ethnicity, gender and socio-economic background.</p><p>o Ensuring that activities aimed at student retention success and progression in are included in within Access and Participation Agreements.</p><p>o Enabling the provision of alternative student finance consistent with the principles of Islamic finance.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2017-04-27T08:14:55.923Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720415/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720415/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720415/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-04-13","Higher Education: Admissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what assessment she has made of the effect of the reduction in the student opportunity allocation announced by the Higher Education Funding Council for England on 15 March 2017 on the Government's target for widening participation in higher education.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","70980"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720416","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-04-25","<p>As at 31 March 2017 there were a total of 54 secondments in the department from the Defra group and external organisations. These are listed below:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Environment Agency</p></td><td><p>27</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Natural England</p></td><td><p>7</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Forestry Commission</p></td><td><p>14</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Affinity Water</p></td><td><p>1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>British Sugar</p></td><td><p>1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Herts &amp; Middlesex Wildlife Trust</p></td><td><p>1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>United Utilities</p></td><td><p>1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Wessex Water</p></td><td><p>1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Westminster City Council</p></td><td><p>1</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-04-25T15:00:55.207Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720416/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720416/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720416/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-04-13","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs: Secondment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how many staff are seconded to her Department; and how many such staff and from which companies and organisations those staff are seconded.","false","Biography information for Tracy Brabin","Batley and Spen","Tracy Brabin","70947"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720417","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-04-24","<p>The Government works with a range of governments and international organisations to conserve endangered species, including elephants, through various fora, including the Convention on International Trade in Endangered Species of Wild Fauna and Flora (CITES). I attended the CITES Conference of Parties in 2016 where the UK played a major role in achieving strong outcomes for elephants, that will help ensure their survival in the wild.</p><p> </p><p>Additionally, the Darwin Initiative is a UK Government grant scheme focussed on preserving animal and plant species and their habitats. This has recently funded a project in Mali that aims to protect elephants by halting and reversing degradation, and habitat loss.</p><p> </p><p>Poaching and trafficking pose a major threat to elephants and other species and demand coordinated international action. The UK is leading the global response to tackling the illegal wildlife trade, and last year we supported Vietnam to host a third successful high level conference on the issue, where new actions to deliver on the commitments agreed at the previous London and Botswana conferences in 2014 and 2015 were secured.</p><p> </p><p>At the conference we announced an additional £13million for tackling the illegal wildlife trade, doubling our existing investment. This funding will support a range of initiatives, including British military training for anti-poaching rangers in key African states and financial support for global action by Interpol and other international organisations involved in the fight against wildlife crime.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-04-24T11:53:53.943Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720417/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720417/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720417/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-04-13","Elephants: Conservation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how the Government intends to secure a long-term future for wild elephants and their natural habitats.","false","Biography information for Corri Wilson","Ayr, Carrick and Cumnock","Corri Wilson","70940"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720418","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-04-25","<p>Under the Cabinet Office’s Governance Code on Public Appointments, the Secretary of State makes appointments to the Board of the Environment Agency after receiving advice from an Advisory Assessment Panel, comprising a Departmental official as Panel chair, a representative from the Environment Agency and an independent Panel member. The Secretary of State also receives advice on appointments from the appropriate Minister at various stages of the process.</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-04-25T11:41:37.477Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720418/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720418/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720418/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-04-13","Environment Agency: Public Appointments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, who makes appointments to the Board of the Environment Agency; which other organisations or individuals provide advice on those appointments; and at what stage of the process such advice is provided.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","70866"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720419","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-04-25","<p>Increasing exports is a top priority for this Government. In October 2016, Defra and the Department for International Trade launched the joint Government and industry ‘UK Food and Drink International Action Plan 2016-2020’ at SIAL in Paris. This details how Government and industry will work in partnership to promote UK food and drink overseas, break down trade barriers and open up new international markets.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-04-25T12:42:35.337Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720419/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720419/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720419/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-04-13","Food: Exports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps her Department is taking to increase exports of British food and drink products.","false","Biography information for John Stevenson","Carlisle","John Stevenson","70891"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720420","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-04-20","<p>Culled carcasses from between 2013 – 2016 were not routinely tested for TB as the RBCT established that approximately one-third of badgers in areas of high incidence of TB in cattle were infected. This year a pilot study was started to explore ways in which badger carcasses obtained from the cull potentially could be used to gather long term information on levels of disease in badgers. A number of carcasses from nine of the areas were sampled and testing methodologies are being piloted. It will be some time before any interim findings on this exploratory undertaking are available.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-04-20T12:19:01.053Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720420/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720420/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720420/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-04-13","Bovine Tuberculosis: Disease Control","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, pursuant to the Answer of 20 December 2016 to Question 57987 and the Answer of 24 March 2017 to Question 66627, how many of the 421 carcasses of badgers have been examined for bovine tuberculosis in line with the Chief Veterinary Officer's advice in his report on the badger culls in 2015.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","70928"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720421","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-04-21","<p>There are currently ten Environment Agency Board Members of whom: (a) six are women; (b) one is from a black or minority ethnic background; (c) none are disabled. We do not have data on their socio-economic backgrounds.</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-04-21T14:02:17.597Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720421/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720421/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720421/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-04-13","Environment Agency: Public Appointments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what proportion of the Environment Agency board are (a) women, (b) from black or minority ethnic backgrounds, (c) disabled or (d) from lower socio-economic backgrounds.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","70722"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720422","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-04-25","<p>The Department of Health is currently conducting a consultation on the availability of gluten-free foods on NHS prescription, and this is expected to close on 22 June 2017.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Government has a policy of supporting our food and farming industry so that we can grow more and sell more British produce.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-04-25T10:30:39.733Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720422/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720422/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720422/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-04-13","Food Supply","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what her Department is doing to improve the supply of UK-produced gluten-free food to consumers.","false","Biography information for Andrew Stephenson","Pendle","Andrew Stephenson","70707"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720423","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-04-24","<p>Commercial dog breeders already require a licence from their local authority in order to operate. The Government has reviewed these controls and has proposed that all licensed dog breeders comply with up to date animal welfare standards. We have also proposed to lower the threshold by which dog breeders will need a licence to three litters a year. Anyone breaching animal welfare standards risks having their licence revoked.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-04-24T15:38:54.447Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720423/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720423/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720423/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-04-13","Dogs: Animal Breeding","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, pursuant to the oral contribution of the Minister of State of 30 March 2017, Official Report, column 480-2, on animal welfare, whether she plans to bring forward legislative proposals prohibiting puppy farms.","false","Biography information for Chris Evans","Islwyn","Chris Evans","70697"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720424","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-04-21","<p>In September, the Secretary of State for Environment announced a ban on trade in worked ivory from the last 70 years, making the UK rules on ivory amongst the toughest in the world. We will consult on these plans.</p><p> </p><p>As part of our consultation, we will also seek evidence on the benefits and impacts of taking further action, and we welcome evidence from all stakeholders in response to our consultation.</p><p> </p><p>I refer the Honorable Member to the debate on 6 February:</p><p><a href="https://hansard.parliament.uk/Commons/2017-02-06/debates/04A0F6F6-C215-49E0-BF6B-87C55BE1AFE9/DomesticIvoryMarket" target="_blank">https://hansard.parliament.uk/Commons/2017-02-06/debates/04A0F6F6-C215-49E0-BF6B-87C55BE1AFE9/DomesticIvoryMarket</a></p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey","70504 ; 70505","2017-04-21T13:32:27.12Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720424/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720424/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720424/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-04-13","Ivory: Sales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what recent steps her Department has taken to fulfil the Government's commitment to closing the UK ivory market.","false","Biography information for Dr Paul Monaghan","Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross","Dr Paul Monaghan","70823"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720425","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-04-25","<p>The Department of Health (DH) is currently conducting a consultation on the availability of gluten-free foods on NHS prescription, and this is expected to close on 22 June 2017.</p><p> </p><p>It is not the role of Government to set food prices or comment on decisions taken by individual companies. We monitor food prices closely using CPI data, but do not monitor the prices of individual product lines. We work to promote transparency and open global markets internationally, as well as a competitive domestic market to help producers and retailers offer the best prices to consumers. Defra ministers and officials regularly meet representatives of the food retailers.</p><p> </p><p>Officials from Defra and Department of Health (DH) meet regularly to discuss a range of issues relating to health and nutrition policy.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","70704 ; 70997","2017-04-25T10:17:46.377Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720425/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720425/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720425/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-04-13","Food: Prices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, whether her Department has made an assessment of the gluten-free food prices compared to overall food prices in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Andrew Stephenson","Pendle","Andrew Stephenson","70703"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720426","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-04-25","<p>The Department of Health (DH) is currently conducting a consultation on the availability of gluten-free foods on NHS prescription, and this is expected to close on 22 June 2017.</p><p> </p><p>It is not the role of Government to set food prices or comment on decisions taken by individual companies. We monitor food prices closely using CPI data, but do not monitor the prices of individual product lines. We work to promote transparency and open global markets internationally, as well as a competitive domestic market to help producers and retailers offer the best prices to consumers. Defra ministers and officials regularly meet representatives of the food retailers.</p><p> </p><p>Officials from Defra and Department of Health (DH) meet regularly to discuss a range of issues relating to health and nutrition policy.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","70703 ; 70997","2017-04-25T10:17:46.437Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720426/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720426/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720426/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-04-13","Food: Prices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what discussions she has had with the Secretary of State for Health on steps to reduce the cost of gluten-free foods for people no longer able to access such foods by prescription.","false","Biography information for Andrew Stephenson","Pendle","Andrew Stephenson","70704"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720427","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-04-24","<p>Usage data for veterinary medicines is not collected and recorded on a national basis. The Government however does collect sales data for all medicines sold in the UK. These data are received from the companies marketing the products at intervals of up to 3 years.</p><p> </p><p>According to the sales data held by the Government, it is estimated that, between the years 2010 and 2015 (the last year for which full sales data for these products is currently available) approximately 19,000 animals each year (across the 4 authorised species of cattle, pigs, sheep and dogs) were treated with products containing pregnant mares’ serum gonadotrophin (PMSG).</p><p> </p><p>The Committee for Medicinal Products for Veterinary Use (CVMP) has also assessed PMSG for its suitability for use in food producing animals and concluded that PMSG offers no risk to the consumer.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-04-24T15:45:41.14Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720427/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720427/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720427/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-04-13","Livestock: Hormone Treatments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what evidence her Department has collected on prevalence of the use of pregnant mares' serum gonadotropin in (a) British farms and (b) meat sold in the UK.","false","Biography information for Kerry McCarthy","Bristol East","Kerry McCarthy","70753"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720428","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-04-24","<p>The Government does not collect information on the number of intensive indoor dairy farms operating in the UK.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-04-24T10:43:44.99Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720428/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720428/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720428/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-04-13","Dairy Farming","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what estimate she has made of the number of intensive indoor dairy farms operating in the UK.","false","Biography information for Peter Kyle","Hove","Peter Kyle","70812"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720429","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-04-24","<p>In order to market a veterinary medicine in the UK, an application must be submitted to the Government to obtain a marketing authorisation. All applications are scientifically assessed against European standards for quality, safety and efficacy to determine the benefits of the product.</p><p> </p><p>This assessment also takes account of any potential risks to the environment, to animals, to people who administer the medicine and to those who may consume produce from treated animals. A product is only granted an authorisation if the benefits of the product outweigh its risks.</p><p> </p><p>The Committee for Medicinal Products for Veterinary Use (CVMP) has also assessed pregnant mares’ serum gonadotrophin (PMSG) for its suitability for use in food producing animals and concluded that PMSG offers no risk to the consumer.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-04-24T15:49:00.56Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720429/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720429/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720429/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-04-13","Livestock: Hormone Treatments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what assessment her Department has made of the potential effects of the use of pregnant mares' serum gonadotropin in meat production on human health.","false","Biography information for Kerry McCarthy","Bristol East","Kerry McCarthy","70754"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720430","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-04-20","<p>The Government continues to undertake a range of analyses to inform the UK’s position for the upcoming EU exit negotiations. We are determined to get the best possible deal for the UK in our negotiations to leave the EU, which allows frictionless trade in goods and services and the opportunity to reach new agreements with countries around the world.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-04-20T12:12:24.813Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720430/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720430/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720430/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-04-13","Agriculture: Exports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what research she has commissioned on the potential effect on agricultural exports of the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Sue Hayman","Workington","Sue Hayman","70780"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720431","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-04-20","<p>Defra has made no specific assessment of the capacity of local authorities to monitor air quality at present or after the UK leaves the EU.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-04-20T16:22:58.22Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720431/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720431/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720431/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-04-13","Air Pollution: Monitoring","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what assessment she has made of the capacity of local authorities to monitor air quality (a) at present and (b) after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Sue Hayman","Workington","Sue Hayman","70781"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720432","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-04-20","<p>The UK Government has, and continues to, put in place a range of measures to protect the marine environment from marine litter. We support the development of initiatives by other countries and organisations where they are consistent with our aims. We will make a decision as to whether to formally participate in this campaign in due course. We are not yet able to specify a date by which this decision will be made.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-04-20T10:31:48.917Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720432/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720432/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720432/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-04-13","Marine Environment: Litter","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, pursuant to the Answer of 3 March 2017 to Question 65619, on marine litter, by when she plans to make a decision on whether the UK will participate in the UN Clean Seas global campaign on marine litter; and if the Government will join that campaign ahead of the UN Oceans Conference on 5 to 9 June 2017.","false","Biography information for Kerry McCarthy","Bristol East","Kerry McCarthy","70647"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720433","Department of Health","false","2017-04-20","<p>Departments are currently working together to understand the impact that withdrawal from the European Union will have across a number of sectors and cross-cutting areas, including the European Food Safety Authority. Options for the future of risk assessment in the United Kingdom are being developed but it is not possible at this time to give an indication of when these options can be shared.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2017-04-20T15:09:44.357Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720433/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720433/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720433/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-04-13","European Food Safety Authority","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, when his Department plans to outline options for the replacement of the European Food Safety Authority after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Calum Kerr","Berwickshire, Roxburgh and Selkirk","Calum Kerr","70613"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720434","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-04-20","<p>A total of £76,322.70 was granted to properties and businesses in Lancashire flooded during the 2013/14 floods. None was paid to or distributed by Lancashire County Council or West Lancashire Borough Council. The table sets out which councils in the county did distribute funds and the total value per council.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Council</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>£</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Fylde Borough Council</p></td><td><p>19,603.20</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Wyre Borough Council</p></td><td><p>10,000.00</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Lancaster City Council</p></td><td><p>17,212.50</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Blackpool Council</p></td><td><p>26,757.00</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>South Ribble Borough Council</p></td><td><p>2,750.00</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-04-20T16:31:57.683Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720434/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720434/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720434/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-04-13","Flood Control: Lancashire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how much grant funding her Department awarded to (a) Lancashire County Council and (b) West Lancashire Borough Council after flooding incidents, by project, in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Rosie Cooper","West Lancashire","Rosie Cooper","70667"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720435","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-04-20","<p>We are investing a record £2.5 billion to better protect 300,000 more properties from flooding by 2021.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>At Budget 2016, the Chancellor of the Exchequer announced a £700 million increase in flood defence and resilience spending. £532m has been allocated to new defences, additional maintenance, new temporary defences and incident management equipment.</p><p> </p><p>Any further allocations will be made by HM Treasury.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-04-20T16:34:30.437Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720435/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720435/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720435/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-04-13","Flood Control: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, when her Department plans to announce its final decision on the allocation of grant funding to flood risk management authorities in response to the floods of Boxing Day 2015.","false","Biography information for Rosie Cooper","West Lancashire","Rosie Cooper","70668"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720436","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-04-25","<p>The details of the government land and property released over the previous financial year will be published as part of the Transparency Review in summer 2017.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-04-25T11:36:02.887Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720436/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720436/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720436/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-04-13","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs: Land","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, with reference to paragraphs 1.296 and 1.297 of the Spending Review and Autumn Statement 2015, what progress her Department has made by estimated capacity of land sold since March 2016 in identifying and disposing of land to meet the Government's commitment.","false","Biography information for Mr Mark Prisk","Hertford and Stortford","Mr Mark Prisk","70676"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720437","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-04-21","<p>In September, the Secretary of State for Environment announced a ban on trade in worked ivory from the last 70 years, making the UK rules on ivory amongst the toughest in the world. We will consult on these plans.</p><p> </p><p>As part of our consultation, we will also seek evidence on the benefits and impacts of taking further action, and we welcome evidence from all stakeholders in response to our consultation.</p><p> </p><p>I refer the Honorable Member to the debate on 6 February:</p><p><a href="https://hansard.parliament.uk/Commons/2017-02-06/debates/04A0F6F6-C215-49E0-BF6B-87C55BE1AFE9/DomesticIvoryMarket" target="_blank">https://hansard.parliament.uk/Commons/2017-02-06/debates/04A0F6F6-C215-49E0-BF6B-87C55BE1AFE9/DomesticIvoryMarket</a></p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey","70505 ; 70823","2017-04-21T13:32:26.98Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720437/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720437/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720437/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-04-13","Ivory: Sales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, whether the consultation on the UK ivory market will look at plans to ban the trade in pre-1947 ivory.","false","Biography information for Dr Paul Monaghan","Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross","Dr Paul Monaghan","70504"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720438","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-04-21","<p>In September, the Secretary of State for Environment announced a ban on trade in worked ivory from the last 70 years, making the UK rules on ivory amongst the toughest in the world. We will consult on these plans.</p><p> </p><p>As part of our consultation, we will also seek evidence on the benefits and impacts of taking further action, and we welcome evidence from all stakeholders in response to our consultation.</p><p> </p><p>I refer the Honorable Member to the debate on 6 February:</p><p><a href="https://hansard.parliament.uk/Commons/2017-02-06/debates/04A0F6F6-C215-49E0-BF6B-87C55BE1AFE9/DomesticIvoryMarket" target="_blank">https://hansard.parliament.uk/Commons/2017-02-06/debates/04A0F6F6-C215-49E0-BF6B-87C55BE1AFE9/DomesticIvoryMarket</a></p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey","70504 ; 70823","2017-04-21T13:32:27.057Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720438/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720438/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720438/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-04-13","Ivory: Sales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, when her Department plans to publish the consultation paper on the UK ivory market.","false","Biography information for Dr Paul Monaghan","Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross","Dr Paul Monaghan","70505"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720439","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-04-21","<p>During the last recruitment campaign for Environment Agency Board Members, the Department received 99 applications for three vacancies on the Board.</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-04-21T13:20:13.787Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720439/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720439/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720439/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-04-13","Environment Agency: Public Appointments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how many applications the board of the Environment Agency received during its last intake.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","70494"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720440","Department of Health","false","2017-04-24","<p>It is expected that the Small Area Health Statistics Unit will submit papers from the project to peer reviewed journals in spring 2017, with publication anticipated a few months after submission.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2017-04-24T16:59:20.273Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720440/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720440/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720440/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-04-13","Incinerators: Health Hazards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, on what date the Incinerators Study by the Small Area Health Statistics Unit will be published.","false","Biography information for Daniel Kawczynski","Shrewsbury and Atcham","Daniel Kawczynski","70483"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720441","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-04-25","<p>The Great Repeal Bill will place existing EU laws on a UK legal basis. Parliament will then be free to amend those laws as it sees fit. The Government is currently considering its approach to future fisheries policy once we leave the EU.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-04-25T16:08:29.73Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720441/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720441/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720441/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-04-13","Fisheries: EU Law","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what EU fisheries legislation her Department plans to (a) replace and (b) preserve before the UK leaves the EU in order to prevent a regulatory deficit.","false","Biography information for Melanie Onn","Great Grimsby","Melanie Onn","70564"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720442","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-04-25","<p>In October 2016, the Chancellor confirmed that the Government will guarantee EU funding for structural and investment fund projects, including the European Maritime and Fisheries Fund (EMFF), signed after the Autumn Statement and which continue after we have left the EU. Funding for projects will be honoured by the Government if they are good value for money and they are in line with domestic strategic priorities.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-04-25T10:27:30.353Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720442/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720442/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720442/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-04-13","European Fisheries Fund: Membership","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, whether the Government plans to continue its membership of the European Fisheries Fund until it expires automatically in 2020.","false","Biography information for Melanie Onn","Great Grimsby","Melanie Onn","70565"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720443","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-04-21","<p>The proportion of fishing trips by UK vessels that were accompanied by an observer in the period from 2013 to 2015 is provided in the table below:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>2015</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Observed trips</p></td><td><p>610</p></td><td><p>755</p></td><td><p>595</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Total trips</p></td><td><p>228,359</p></td><td><p>228,413</p></td><td><p>222,015</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>% observed trips</p></td><td><p>0.3%</p></td><td><p>0.3%</p></td><td><p>0.3%</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-04-21T13:40:04.907Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720443/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720443/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720443/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-04-13","Fisheries: Monitoring","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, pursuant to the Answer of 20 October 2016 to Question 48853, what proportion of the total fishing trips were accompanied by a fisheries observer in (a) 2013, (b) 2014 and (c) 2015.","false","Biography information for Melanie Onn","Great Grimsby","Melanie Onn","70566"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720444","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-04-25","<p>The budget for Core Defra’s procurement function for each of the financial years from 2010-11 is shown below.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>£000</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2010-11</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2011-12</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2012-13</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2013-14</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2014-15</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2015-16</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2016-17</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Budget</strong></p></td><td><p>4,475</p></td><td><p>3,854</p></td><td><p>3,338</p></td><td><p>3,151</p></td><td><p>2,599</p></td><td><p>4,060</p></td><td><p>3,560</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p><strong> </strong></p><p>A corporate services transformation programme is ongoing within Defra. The first stage of this transformation for procurement saw teams from Animal &amp; Plant Health Agency, Natural England and Marine Maritime Organisation transferred into Defra on 1<sup>st</sup> October 2014. This meant a 57% increase in headcount in core Defra, and resulted in increased procurement budgets for 2015-16 and 2016-17.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-04-25T15:25:44.883Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720444/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720444/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720444/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-04-13","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, pursuant to the Answer of 27 February 2017 to Question 64997, on procurement, what estimate she has made of the total budget for managing procurement in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","70554"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720445","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-04-21","<p>The number of eligible farm businesses in receipt of the Single Payment Scheme for 2014–2015 and the Basic Payment Scheme for 2015-16 and the total value of these in 2014-15 and 2016-16 are summarised in the table below:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>2014-2015</p></td><td><p>2015-2016</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Boston and Skegness Constituency</p></td><td><p>318</p></td><td><p>307</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Lincolnshire</p></td><td><p>2,894</p></td><td><p>2,765</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>England</p></td><td><p>87,114</p></td><td><p>83,751</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Total value</p></td><td><p>£1,403,117,653</p></td><td><p>£1,577,170,673</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-04-21T13:55:34.567Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720445/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720445/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720445/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-04-13","Agriculture: Subsidies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how many farms in (a) Boston and Skegness constituency, (b) Lincolnshire and (c) England are in receipt of EU subsidies; and how much the total value of the subsidies was in (i) 2014-15 and (ii) 2015-16.","false","Biography information for Matt Warman","Boston and Skegness","Matt Warman","70574"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720446","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-04-20","<p>Currently, the Pets Database holds information on pet movements into GB on approved routes gathered by transport companies. Since mid-2015 the Animal and Plant Health Agency (APHA) has been piloting a parallel system to establish the level of accuracy of data available from the Pets Database. This has identified that more dogs are travelling under the Pet Travel Scheme than previously indicated by the Pets Database data, and this number was presented in PQ62238. Based on this finding, APHA is now working on a new permanent system to capture accurately all the required data without placing an unrealistic burden on carriers.</p><p> </p><p>The information that APHA has provided in response to PQ66537 is a true reflection of the information that is held on the Pets Database, as supplied by third parties.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-04-20T13:59:49.207Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720446/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720446/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720446/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-04-13","Dogs: Imports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, pursuant to the Answer of 22 March 2017 to Question 66537, for what reason the numbers of dogs imported into the UK from each origin country, as presented in Annex A, do not add up to the number recorded on APHA's system of dogs entering the UK non-commercially under the Pets Travel Scheme, as stated in the Answer of 30 January 2017 to Question 62238.","false","Biography information for Mr Alistair Carmichael","Orkney and Shetland","Mr Alistair Carmichael","70622"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720447","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-04-25","<p>The Department does not collate information on the number of pregnant cows slaughtered annually.</p><p> </p><p>The Government encourages the highest standards of welfare at both slaughter and during transport. It is illegal under the welfare in transport legislation to transport any pregnant animal where more than 90% of the gestation period has elapsed; this includes transporting pregnant animals to slaughterhouses. For TB infected cattle, most are removed from farms within 10 working days of disclosure. However, since September 2015 owners of heavily pregnant TB affected cows have had the option of keeping the animal on farm until it has calved, up to a maximum of 28 days.</p><p> </p><p>The slaughter of pregnant animals is not itself currently covered by additional specific welfare requirements. The European Food Safety Authority is due to release a scientific report on this issue in the near future.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","70599","2017-04-25T13:16:51.677Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720447/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720447/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720447/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-04-13","Slaughterhouses: Cattle","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, whether her Department collates information on the number of pregnant cows slaughtered annually.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","70598"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720448","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-04-25","<p>The Department does not collate information on the number of pregnant cows slaughtered annually.</p><p> </p><p>The Government encourages the highest standards of welfare at both slaughter and during transport. It is illegal under the welfare in transport legislation to transport any pregnant animal where more than 90% of the gestation period has elapsed; this includes transporting pregnant animals to slaughterhouses. For TB infected cattle, most are removed from farms within 10 working days of disclosure. However, since September 2015 owners of heavily pregnant TB affected cows have had the option of keeping the animal on farm until it has calved, up to a maximum of 28 days.</p><p> </p><p>The slaughter of pregnant animals is not itself currently covered by additional specific welfare requirements. The European Food Safety Authority is due to release a scientific report on this issue in the near future.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","70598","2017-04-25T13:16:51.74Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720448/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720448/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720448/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-04-13","Slaughterhouses: Cattle","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what her Department's policy is on the slaughter of pregnant cows.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","70599"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720449","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-04-25","<p>As at 31 March 2017 the proportion of staff employed in the department is shown below:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong> </strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Headcount</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>%</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Full-Time permanent staff</p></td><td><p>1587</p></td><td><p>76.6%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Part-Time permanent staff</p></td><td><p>265</p></td><td><p>12.8%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Fixed / Short Term appointments employed for less than two years</p></td><td><p>98</p></td><td><p>4.7%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Agency Basis staff</p></td><td><p>121</p></td><td><p>5.8%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Zero-Hours</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>0.0%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Total</p></td><td><p>2071</p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>It is not Defra Policy to employ staff on “Zero-Hours” contracts.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-04-25T15:44:00.01Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720449/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720449/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720449/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-04-13","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs: Conditions of Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how many and what proportion of staff employed by her Department are employed on a contract which is (a) full-time permanent, (b) part-time permanent, (c) for less than two years' duration, (d) on an agency basis and (e) zero-hours.","false","Biography information for Rob Marris","Wolverhampton South West","Rob Marris","70462"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720450","Department of Health","false","2017-04-20","<p>The Government has not yet had any discussions with the European Food Safety Authority (EFSA) on its future remit in the United Kingdom. The Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, the Food Standard Agency and other Government Departments/bodies currently work with the EFSA on a range of issues including public health, food safety, plant and animal health and welfare. Government departments are working together to ensure that we will continue to have a collaborative relationship with the EFSA post-exit and that UK risk management decisions will continue to be based on robust scientific evidence.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2017-04-20T17:02:12.94Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720450/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720450/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720450/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-04-13","European Food Safety Authority","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what discussions he has had with representatives of the European Food Safety Authority on its future remit in the UK.","false","Biography information for Calum Kerr","Berwickshire, Roxburgh and Selkirk","Calum Kerr","70446"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720451","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-04-20","<p>Defra is working closely with the Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy at ministerial and official level, to ensure the industrial strategy supports the agri-food sector.</p><p> </p><p>The agri-food sector contributes £110 billion per year to our economy and is a big employer in every region of the UK, so is well placed to support growth across the whole country. We will be working with the agri-food sector to develop an industrial strategy that delivers a world-leading food, farming and fishing nation that grows more, sells more and exports more food around the world.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-04-20T12:03:26.177Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720451/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720451/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720451/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-04-13","Food: Industry","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what discussions she has had with the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy on how the Government's industrial strategy will support food producers.","false","Biography information for Calum Kerr","Berwickshire, Roxburgh and Selkirk","Calum Kerr","70447"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720452","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-04-20","<p>In the most recently published figures from Agriculture in the UK, production to supply ratio for all food is 61 per cent, and for indigenous food 76 per cent. These figures have been relatively constant over the previous 10 years.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>All food %</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Indigenous type food %</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011</p></td><td><p>64</p></td><td><p>78</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>63</p></td><td><p>77</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>60</p></td><td><p>73</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>62</p></td><td><p>76</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>61</p></td><td><p>76</p></td></tr></tbody></table></p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>The next publication of Agriculture in the UK will be on 25 May 2017 and this will include the 2016 production to supply figures.</p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr></tbody></table>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-04-20T15:40:40.047Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720452/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720452/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720452/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-04-13","Food Supply","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what the UK food self-sufficiency was in (a) 2011, (b) 2012, (c) 2013, (d) 2014, (e) 2015 and (f) 2016.","false","Biography information for Jeremy Lefroy","Stafford","Jeremy Lefroy","70370"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720453","Home Office","false","2017-04-27","<p>The agricultural sector is important to the United Kingdom and we take concerns of labour shortages seriously.</p><p> </p><p>For the time being the United Kingdom remains part of the European Union and freedom of movement continues. The latest labour market statistics, for the year ending December 2016, show that there were 190,000 more EU workers in the UK workforce than a year earlier.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-04-27T09:42:02.317Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720453/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720453/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720453/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-04-13","Seasonal Agricultural Workers' Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment she has made of the potential merits of reintroducing the Seasonal Agricultural Workers Scheme to ensure that UK agriculture has sufficient seasonal staff available to harvest, process and pack fruit and vegetables.","false","Biography information for Jeremy Lefroy","Stafford","Jeremy Lefroy","70371"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720454","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-04-24","<p>Ministers and officials in Defra have had regular dialogue with Ministers and officials in the Home Office and Ministry of Justice. The issue of sentencing was discussed most recently in the context of two Private Members Bills tabled on this issue.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-04-24T15:09:55.423Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720454/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720454/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720454/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-04-13","Animal Welfare: Sentencing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what discussions she has had with the Secretary of State for Justice and the Home Secretary on increasing the maximum custodial sentence for acts of animal cruelty to five years imprisonment; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mrs Madeleine Moon","Bridgend","Mrs Madeleine Moon","70379"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720455","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-04-21","<p>There are no current plans to amend the Water Industry (Schemes for Adoption of Private Sewers) Regulations 2011, which provided for the transfer of eligible private sewers and lateral drains to water and sewerage companies on 1 October 2011 and the transfer of pumping stations on 1 October 2016.</p><p> </p><p>The last Government carried out an extensive review of private sewer ownership, including a full public consultation on the draft regulations. The issues raised during the consultation were considered in preparing the final regulations.</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey","70302 ; 70303","2017-04-21T11:11:18.477Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720455/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720455/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720455/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-04-13","Sewers: Regulation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, whether she plans to amend the private sewer transfer regulations to allow the transfer of private sewerage pumps to be regulated water companies by residents in a different curtilage.","false","Biography information for Chris Evans","Islwyn","Chris Evans","70301"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720456","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-04-21","<p>There are no current plans to amend the Water Industry (Schemes for Adoption of Private Sewers) Regulations 2011, which provided for the transfer of eligible private sewers and lateral drains to water and sewerage companies on 1 October 2011 and the transfer of pumping stations on 1 October 2016.</p><p> </p><p>The last Government carried out an extensive review of private sewer ownership, including a full public consultation on the draft regulations. The issues raised during the consultation were considered in preparing the final regulations.</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey","70301 ; 70303","2017-04-21T11:11:18.523Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720456/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720456/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720456/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-04-13","Sewers: Regulation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, whether she plans to amend the private sewer transfer regulations to bring all remaining private sewerage systems under the ownership of regulated water companies.","false","Biography information for Chris Evans","Islwyn","Chris Evans","70302"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720457","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-04-21","<p>There are no current plans to amend the Water Industry (Schemes for Adoption of Private Sewers) Regulations 2011, which provided for the transfer of eligible private sewers and lateral drains to water and sewerage companies on 1 October 2011 and the transfer of pumping stations on 1 October 2016.</p><p> </p><p>The last Government carried out an extensive review of private sewer ownership, including a full public consultation on the draft regulations. The issues raised during the consultation were considered in preparing the final regulations.</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey","70301 ; 70302","2017-04-21T11:11:18.587Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720457/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720457/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720457/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-04-13","Sewers: Regulation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, whether she plans to amend the private sewer transfer regulations to allow residents of small flat complexes to transfer ownership of their existing private sewerage systems to regulated water companies.","false","Biography information for Chris Evans","Islwyn","Chris Evans","70303"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720458","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-04-25","<p>The UK monitors events in Bahrain closely. We continue to raise concerns about human rights with the Bahraini authorities, both in private and in public. We encourage anyone with concerns about their treatment in detention to report these directly to the Ombudsman.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-04-25T12:27:46.457Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720458/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720458/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720458/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-04-13","Sayed Alwadaei","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, whether he has made representations to his Bahraini counterpart on the harassment of family members of Sayed Al Wadaei.","false","Biography information for Margaret Ferrier","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Margaret Ferrier","70313"
